## -------------------------------

@node "Main_INSTALL" "Installing the program"
To install COMPACT to your harddisk, you can simply double click to the
install icon, which starts an Installer script. If you want to install
the player manually, please perform the following steps:

Create a directory and copy the whole directory of the distribution to
this new drawer (with all subdirectories).
Now copy the iff.library in the "libs" drawer to your LIBS: drawer, as
long as it isn't already there.
If you receive a keyfile with the distribution (see @{"Registering" LINK Intro_REGISTER}), you
have to copy it to the S: drawer.
Now you must set the following two tooltypes of COMPACT's icon, which are
important to run the player correctly:

	@{"DEVICE" LINK "Tool_DEVICE"}
	@{"UNIT" LINK "Tool_DEVICE"}


Additionally the following libraries must be present in your LIBS-drawer:
   amigaguide.library		V34 or higher
   asl.library			V38 or higher
   commodities.library		V37 or higher
   diskfont.library		V37 or higher
   mathieeesingtrans.library	V37 or higher
All these libraries comes together with the Workbench, so every Amiga user
who runs Amiga-OS 3.0 should possess it.

The font "Helvetica 18" should be present in the FONTS: drawer. Nevertheless,
when it is not available, COMPACT will run, but on an own custom screens with
the high Y-size resolution the gui will look not as good as with this font.
Because it is included with Workbench 3.0, everybody should possess it.
@endnode

## -------------------------------

@node "Main_START" "How to start the player"
You can start the player via Workbench or the Shell. No arguments are needed,
because all important settings are stored into the tooltypes of its icon!

Therefore, the tooltypes are read also when the player is started from the
shell! It is important that you don't delete the icon, because otherwise the
internal defaults are used, and they refer to the devicename / unit too,
which are very drive-specific!

@{B}The following tooltypes are supported:@{UB}

   @{"APPICON" LINK Tool_APPICON}
   @{"CX_POPKEY" LINK Tool_CXPOPKEY}
   @{"CX_PRIORITY" LINK Tool_CXPRIORITY}
   @{"CX_POPUP" LINK Tool_CXPOPUP}
@{FG shine}*@{FG text}  @{"DEVICE" LINK Tool_DEVICE}
   @{"DONOTWAIT" LINK Tool_DONOTWAIT}
   @{"HOT_EJECT" LINK Tool_HOT}
   @{"HOT_PAUSE" LINK Tool_HOT}
   @{"HOT_PLAY" LINK Tool_HOT}
   @{"HOT_SEARCH+" LINK Tool_HOT}
   @{"HOT_SEARCH-" LINK Tool_HOT}
   @{"HOT_SKIP+" LINK Tool_HOT}
   @{"HOT_SKIP-" LINK Tool_HOT}
   @{"HOT_STOP" LINK Tool_HOT}
   @{"PUBNAME" LINK Tool_PUBNAME}
   @{"SCREEN_LACED" LINK Tool_SCRLACED}
@{FG shine}*@{FG text}  @{"UNIT" LINK Tool_DEVICE}

If a tooltype is missing or it is between brackets, its internal default
will be used.

NOTE: Tooltypes marked with a @{FG shine}"*"@{FG text} are important and should be set correctly,
before you start the player the first time (will be done automatically, if
COMPACT was installed with the Installer script).
The "PATH"-entry in the configfile (see below) should be set correctly right
after the first start of the player, which can be done by selecting a path
using "@{"Save-/Load-path..." LINK m2path}" in the menu "Settings", and after that
selecting "@{"Save configuration" LINK m2save}" in the same menu!


Other features of the player are stored in a configuration file like mentioned
above, which can be saved from the menu "Settings / Save configuration". This
file has the name "Compact.config" and is a plain ASCII file, but it is not
recommended to edit it manually!

@{B}The following settings are stored in it:@{UB}

   @{"CLOCK" LINK Tool_CLOCK}
   @{"COLCYCLE" LINK Tool_COLCYCLE}
   @{"EJECTOVERDRIVE" LINK Tool_EJECT}
   @{"FILENOTES" LINK Tool_FILENOTE}
   @{"FULLPALETTE" LINK Tool_FULLPAL}
   @{"IFFNAME" LINK Tool_IFFNAME}
   @{"LOADDEFPROG" LINK Tool_LOADDEFPRG}
@{FG shine}*@{FG text}  @{"PATH" LINK Tool_PATH}
   @{"PLAYSTART" LINK Tool_PLAYSTART}
   @{"QUITSTOP" LINK Tool_QUITSTOP}
   @{"SEARCHSECS" LINK Tool_SEARCHSEC}
   @{"STARTEVERYTRACK" LINK Tool_STARTET}
   @{"TASKPRI" LINK Tool_TASKPRI}
   @{"TITLEBAR" LINK Tool_TITLEBAR}
   @{"TOP10MAX" LINK Tool_TOP10MAX}
   @{"TOP10SAVEONCE" LINK Tool_TOP10SAVEONCE}
   @{"TOTALTIME" LINK Tool_TOTTIME}
@endnode

@node "Tool_APPICON" "Tooltype:  APPICON"
Possible arguments:	<name>
Internal default  :
Example		  :	APPICON=CD-Player

When you hide the player, it can be controlled by the program "Exchange" and
the hotkeys (see tooltype @{"CX_POPKEY" LINK Tool_CXPOPKEY}). If you want to make use of the appicon
feature, you must define its name with this tooltype. If you don't declare it
or you set it between brackets like for example @{B}(APPICON=Compact)@{UB}, no
appicon will appear on the Workbench.

If you use this tooltype to get an appicon, you can use it as follows:
- Double click on the appicon to bring the player's window back again.
- Take an icon of an IFF-picture and let it fall to the appicon.
  Herewith the player opens a screen with your picture being the background
  of the player-window (see menu "@{"SPECIAL/OWN SCREEN" LINK m3scre}"). When you select
  more than one icon, only the first will be used.
@endnode

@node "Tool_CLOCK" "Config-file entry:  CLOCK"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	YES
Example		  :	CLOCK=YES
Defined via menu  :	Settings / Clock in display

When this entry is set to "YES", the actual time can be shown in the
display for the CD-time in the main-window.
@endnode

@node "Tool_COLCYCLE" "Config-file entry:  COLCYCLE"
Possible arguments:	a/b/c/d
Internal default  :	0/0/1/0
Example		  :	COLCYCLE=0/0/1/0
Defined via menu  :	@{"Special / Change colours" LINK m3colo}

With this entry the mode of the colour-cycling feature is stored. Because
it is saved along with the other settings to the config file, you normally
don't want to edit it manually. For your information, here are the contents
of the parts called a, b, c and d:

a:	Mode of color cycling. 0=off, 1=on.
b:	Direction of the cycle. 0=forwards, 1=backwards.
c:	Speed of the cycle. Can go from 1 (=slow) to 10 (=fast).
d:	"D" IS NOT USED FOR THE MOMENT! LEAVE IT TO 0 AS LONG AS IT IS
	NOT IMPLEMENTED!
@endnode

@node "Tool_CXPOPKEY" "Tooltype:  CX_POPKEY"
Possible arguments:	<hotkey>
Internal default  :	lshift lcommand c
Example		  :	CX_POPKEY=rshift tab

With this tooltype you can set the hotkey for COMPACT.
The player can be hidden by the menu "Projects/Hide" or by the control
program for all commodities (Exchange). If hidden, the player continues to
work as normal, but to switch back to the mode with a window, you have to
use the program "Exchange", or a hotkey combination which is defined by the
tooltype above.

You can use this hotkey also to bring COMPACT's screen and window to the
front. This can be needed when many windows are in front of the player and
you want to use it quickly.

INFO: Regardless of the player's status (hidden or visible), you can use
several other hotkeys to control COMPACT from every program's window/screen,
as long as this program supports multitasking! Please read @{"here" LINK Tool_HOT} to get more
informations about this.


@{B}ONE OR MORE OF THE FOLLOWING QUALIFIERS CAN BE USED FOR ALL HOTKEYS:@{UB}

QUALIFIER:	DESCRIPTION:
----------	------------
lalt		Left Alt
ralt		Right Alt
alt		Left or right Alt
lshift		Left shift
rshift		Right shift
shift		Left or right Shift
lcommand	Left Amiga
rcommand	Right Amiga
control		Control
ctrl		Control

@{B}BEHIND YOUR QUALIFIER(S) THERE MUST BE ONE KEY, WHICH CAN BE ANY NORMAL
CHARACTER OR ONE OF THE FOLLOWING:@{UB}

backspace,  del,  return,  enter,  space,  tab,  up,  down,  left,  right,
f1 - f10,  esc,  help
@endnode

@node "Tool_CXPRIORITY" "Tooltype:  CX_PRIORITY"
Possible arguments:	<nr>
Internal default  :	0
Example		  :	CX_PRIORITY=0

Here you can set the commodity-priority of the player. In most cases you
don't want to change this.

Please note: This is NOT the taskpriority of the player!
@endnode

@node "Tool_CXPOPUP" "Tooltype:  CX_POPUP"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	YES
Example		  :	CX_POPUP=YES

With this tooltype you can define whether COMPACT opens its window at the
start or not. When set to "NO", the player will be in the hidden mode, so
to see it you will need either the program "Exchange", use the hotkey
combination defined in the tooltype @{"CX_POPKEY" LINK Tool_CXPOPKEY}, or using the appicon, if
you specified it (see tooltype @{"APPICON" LINK Tool_APPICON}).
@endnode

@node "Tool_DEVICE" "Tooltypes:  DEVICE, UNIT"
*** DEVICE: ***
Possible arguments:	<xyz.device>
Internal default  :	amiquest.device
Example		  :	DEVICE=amiquest.device

*** UNIT: ***
Possible arguments:	<nr>
Internal default  :	2
Example		  :	UNIT=2

These two tooltypes are very important, because they are needed for the
communication between the player and the CD-ROM drive. The documentation of
your CD-ROM driver software should contain the information about how to set
these tooltypes correctly. For example, when using the Archos Overdrive you
have to set these to DEVICE=amiquest.device and UNIT=2 (the first version of
this software doesn't function correctly with the player-commands, so please
use the highest version you can get. The version used by myself is V11.2)

To get an idea about which device-names are available, a small tool with the
name "@{"showdevices" LINK showdevices}" comes along with this player, which outputs all devices
available in the system, which could be used for a CD-Rom.
Please make sure that you have mounted your CD-ROM driver _before_ starting
this utility and/or COMPACT! In most cases you have to start the driver in
the drawer "SYS:Storage/DosDrivers", except the case that its icon is in the
directory "SYS:Devs/DosDrivers", where it is mounted automatically while
booting your Amiga.
@endnode

@node "Tool_DONOTWAIT" "Tooltype:  DONOTWAIT"
When the icon of COMPACT is in the drawer SYS:WBSTARTUP while booting your
Amiga, and this tooltype is present, the Workbench starts the player and
continues the process of loading programs etc.
Otherwise, when you don't specify this tooltype, the Workbench interrupts the
loading and waits as long as you exit the player. Therefore you always should
set this tooltype when COMPACT is in the WBSTARTUP directory.
@endnode

@node "Tool_EJECT" "Config-file entry:  EJECTOVERDRIVE"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	NO
Example		  :	EJECTOVERDRIVE=YES
Defined via menu  :	Settings / Overdrive-"Eject"

Herewith you can decide, whether the eject-function should use the standard
SCSI command or the little bit different command for the Archos Overdrive.
When the eject function produces an error or does not work as it should, you
can try to use the other setting.
@endnode

@node "Tool_FILENOTE" "Config-file entry:  FILENOTE"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	YES
Example		  :	FILENOTE=YES
Defined via menu  :	Settings / Save with filenote

When a CD is inserted, you can input the name of the CD, the track-names etc.
These inputs are saved to disk under a filename which is built from the
program, and they look for example like this one: "ID09464106580439". Very
readable, isn't it?
This entry now allows you to have a quick look, what this filename stands
for. When you set it to "YES", every filename which is saved like the example
above, gets a comment which looks for example like this: "Genesis - Abacab".
As you can see, this filenote is built from the composer and the name of the
CD, divided by a "-".

You can now quickly view the contents of your directory which contains all
the files, by typing the following commands into a shell:

	cd YOUR_DIRECTORY
	list ID#? lformat "%n  %c"

For "YOUR_DIRECTORY" you must of course type in the path of your directory,
which contains all the ID-files (can be selected by the "@{"PATH" LINK Tool_PATH}"-entry)!

Please note, that you can use the @{"database" LINK m3data} of COMPACT to get a very better
overview of your CDs!
@endnode

@node "Tool_FULLPAL" "Config-file entry:  FULLPALETTE"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	NO
Example		  :	FULLPALETTE=YES
Defined via menu  :	@{"Settings / Full palette" LINK m2full}

When COMPACT runs on its own custom screen, you can load a background picture
behind all gadgets. When this entry is set to "YES", all colours of this
picture will be used. In this case the first four colours are overwritten by
the palette of the picture, and this could cause an ugly display of the
gadgets.
Otherwise, when you set this entry to "NO" or omit it, the first four
colours are not overwritten by the picture's palette, so the display of the
gadgets will be okay. When you want to create pictures for the background of
COMPACT, you should not use the first four colours, so you can leave
this entry to "NO" and all colours are looking good.
@endnode

@node "Tool_TOP10MAX" "Config-file entry:  TOP10MAX"
Possible arguments:	<nr>
Internal default  :	10
Example		  :	TOP10MAX=10

It defines, how many entries are visible in the statistic window, in which
the TOP10 of your most heared CDs are displayed. So you can make for example
a TOP50, if prefer to see more than 10 entries.

The value of this entry can be set in the @{"statistic window" LINK Statisti}, which can be
opened from the window of COMPACT's @{"database" LINK m3data}.
@endnode

@node "Tool_TOP10SAVEONCE" "Config-file entry:  TOP10SAVEONCE"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	NO
Example		  :	TOP10SAVEONCE=YES
Defined via menu  :	Settings / Save TOP10 immediately

This switch decides, whether or not the TOP10 file will be saved immediately
after a change in the memory. When set to YES, the TOP10 file will
be saved only, when you quit COMPACT.
In the memory, the data about the TOP10 is always actual; this switch
only is for controlling the behavior of the save routine.
@endnode

@node "Tool_HOT" "Hotkeys to control COMPACT from nearly everywhere"
For the following functions you can use hotkeys. You can define the hotkey
for each function via a tooltype, or use its internal default by omitting it.
These hotkeys can be used from every program, window or screen, as long as it
runs in the multitasking environment! You don't have to activate the window
of COMPACT to use these hotkeys! Simply press it while for example painting a
picture or writing a text in your editor.
These hotkeys can be used always; they are independent whether COMPACT is
hidden or not. Please read @{"here" LINK Tool_CXPOPKEY} for the valid qualifiers you can use for all
hotkeys.
Please note, that this doesn't work, as long as a file-requester or a
requester the user must respond is opened from the player!

The following hotkeys can be used; they are defined by the tooltypes:


@{U}Tooltype:	Internal default:	Description:@{UU}

HOT_EJECT	lshift lcommand e	@{"EJECT" LINK MaWiEjec}
HOT_PAUSE	lshift lcommand u	@{"PAUSE" LINK MaWiPaus}
HOT_PLAY	lshift lcommand p	@{"PLAY" LINK MaWiPlay}
HOT_SEARCH+	lshift lcommand up	@{"SEARCH FORWARDS" LINK MaWiSea+}
HOT_SEARCH-	lshift lcommand down	@{"SEARCH BACKWARDS" LINK MaWiSea-}
HOT_SKIP+	lshift lcommand right	@{"SKIP FORWARDS" LINK MaWiSki+}
HOT_SKIP-	lshift lcommand left	@{"SKIP BACKWARDS" LINK MaWiSki-}
HOT_STOP	lshift lcommand s	@{"STOP" LINK MaWiStop}

CX_POPKEY	lshift lcommand c	When COMPACT is hidden its window
					appears. Doesn't work, when COMPACT
					is set to "inactive" via Exchange!
@endnode

@node "Tool_IFFNAME" "Config-file entry:  IFFNAME"
Possible arguments:	<iff_picture_name>
Internal default  :	(no picture)
Example		  :	IFFNAME=progdir:Compact.iff_L_Plasma
Defined via menu  :	Special / Change IFF-picture

Here you can set the name of the IFF picture, which should be displayed when
you select "@{"Own screen" LINK m3scre}" in the menu. When you select a wrong name, or the
file is not of the required type, no picture will be displayed.
@endnode

@node "Tool_LOADDEFPRG" "Config-file entry:  LOADDEFPROG"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	YES
Example		  :	LOADDEFPROG=YES
Defined via menu  :	Settings / Load default prog.

In several cases you don't want to hear _all_ tracks of a CD, because only a
few of all tracks are your favorites. For this reason you can use the
@{"programming feature" LINK MaWiProg} of COMPACT. Here you can decide, which tracks you want
to hear and in which order. After you have selected all this tracks, you can
save this program to disk with a filename, or you can choose the option
"Save default program". Here the program is saved in the same directory your
track-name-files are, and it gets the same ID-number of the actual CD, but
with the prefix "PR".

When this entry is set to "YES", every time you insert a CD for which a
"default program"-file exists, your favorite program-selection will be read
and you only have to click to the "Program"-button to get your program
ready to start.

Please note, that this entry have to be set to YES when you want to use a
default program at an immediately play after starting the player! For this
feature please read @{"here" LINK Tool_PLAYSTART}.
@endnode

@node "Tool_PATH" "Config-file entry:  PATH"
Possible arguments:	<directory_path>
Internal default  :	PROGDIR:AudioCD-IDs
Example		  :	PATH=dh0:data/MyDrawerForAudioCD
Defined via menu  :	Settings / Save-/Load-path...

When a CD is inserted, you can input the name of the CD, the track-names etc.
These inputs are saved to disk under a filename which is built from the
program (see @{"ID-Number" LINK IDnumber}). With this entry you can decide, which path is
used for containing all the files of your CD-inputs.

This entry should be set correctly right after the first start of COMPACT,
because otherwise all these files are stored into the directory "AudioCD-IDs",
which is in the same drawer as the player is. After saving the settings
via "Save configuration" in the menu "Settings", this path will be used
every time.
@endnode

@node "Tool_PLAYSTART" "Config-file entry:  PLAYSTART"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	NO
Example		  :	PLAYSTART=YES
Defined via menu  :	Settings / "PLAY" after start

With this one set to "YES", the player will start to play immediately after
being started, as long as a audio CD is into the drive.
When the entry @{"LOADDEFPROG" LINK Tool_LOADDEFPRG} is set to YES, and there exists a default program
for the actual CD, COMPACT will use this automatically! So you can define,
which tracks are to be played after starting the player.
@endnode

@node "Tool_PUBNAME" "Tooltype:  PUBNAME"
Possible arguments:	<public_screen_name>
Internal default  :	Workbench
Example		  :	PUBNAME=DOPUS.1
Can be changed via menu.

With this tooltype you can decide, which public screen will be used for the
window of COMPACT, as long as it doesn't use an own custom screen. Please
note, that a minimum of 4 colours is required to work comfortably with
COMPACT! The names of public screens are case-sensitiv!

While COMPACT is running you can jump from one public screen to another one
with the menu "@{"Special / PubScreen-Jump" LINK m3pubs}".
@endnode

@node "Tool_QUITSTOP" "Config-file entry:  QUITSTOP"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	NO
Example		  :	QUITSTOP=YES
Defined via menu  :	Settings / "STOP" before quit

Normally, when you quit the program, the CD-ROM drive gets no command to stop
playing, and therefore continues with playing music. When you start COMPACT
again after quitting it, there is no music-interrupt and the time-display is
updated immediately.
When you set this entry to "YES", COMPACT will send a stop-command to the
drive before reacting to the quit.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SCRLACED" "Tooltype:  SCRLACED"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	YES
Example		  :	SCRLACED=NO

As stated in the setting "@{"IFFNAME" LINK Tool_IFFNAME}" for the config-file, you can switch
to an own custom screen with an user-selectable background picture.
Normally, the height of the picture decides, whether the screen is in a high
(512 lines) or low (256 lines) Y-size resolution.
If your IFF-file is in the wrong format or the file is not present, NO back-
ground picture will be used, and the screen opens with 4 colours only. In
this case the Y-size resolution depends on this tooltype: set it to "YES" to
get a high resolution, or to "NO" to get the low resolution. The X-size of
the own custom screen will be 640 always!

PLEASE NOTE:  When the high resolution is used, COMPACT tries to use the
"helvetica 18"-font, otherwise "topaz 8" will be used. If "helvetica 18" is
not available (it comes with the Workbench, so everybody should possess it),
the "topaz 8" will be used in the high resolution too, but then the gui will
not look as good as with "helvetica 18".
@endnode

@node "Tool_SEARCHSEC" "Config-file entry:  SEARCHSECS"
Possible arguments:	<seconds>
Internal default  :	10
Example		  :	SEARCHSECS=5
Defined via menu  :	Settings / SEARCH-seconds...

When a SEARCH button is pressed (backwards or forwards), the seconds
specified here are used to jump backwards or forwards.
Note that only seconds ranging from 5 to 120 are recognized, otherwise the
internal default will be used!
@endnode

@node "Tool_STARTET" "Config-file entry:  STARTEVERYTRACK"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	NO
Example		  :	STARTEVERYTRACK=YES
Defined via menu  :	Settings / Start at every track

In most cases, you never will need this one and leave it to "NO".
Normally, when a track is finished and the next starts to play, no command
will be sent to the drive and COMPACT only reacts on this by updating the
CD-time display. When you set this entry to "YES", the player will send
a new PLAY-command for this new track.
The reason for this implementation is, that one of my drives used for testing
automatically stops after 14 minutes and 32 seconds, as long as it doesn't
receives any play-command etc. To prevent this, one can use this entry.
If the track plays longer than the time above, this error can't be avoided.
Drawback of this function is, that a short stammer can be heard at every
start of a new track.
@endnode

@node "Tool_TASKPRI" "Config-file entry:  TASKPRI"
Possible arguments:	-1, 0, 1
Internal default  :	0
Example		  :	TASKPRI=0
Defined via menu  :	Settings / Taskpriority / ...

Herewith you can set the taskpriority of COMPACT. When you find, that for
example your raytracer eats too many CPU-time, and the player therefore can't
react correctly on your commands, or can't update the CD-time display in the
right time, you can change it here. In almost all cases the default value
of 0 will be okay.
@endnode

@node "Tool_TITLEBAR" "Config-file entry:  TITLEBAR"
Possible arguments:	YES, NO
Internal default  :	NO
Example		  :	TITLEBAR=YES
Defined via menu  :	Settings / Show screen title bar

When set to YES, you will see the title bar of the own custom screen. This is
useful when you want to see the help strings for the gadgets, which appears
in the title bar of a screen. On a public screen like the Workbench this
setting has no function!

PLEASE NOTE: The own custom screen can be moved via the title bar also when
it is not visible! At the top of the screen there exists an one pixel high
line which can be used to move the screen, and at the right side of it there
exists the background-gadget for the screen.
@endnode

@node "Tool_TOTTIME" "Config-file entry:  TOTALTIME"
Possible arguments:	PROG, ALL
Internal default  :	PROG
Example		  :	TOTALTIME=PROG
Defined via menu  :	Settings / TotalTime = Prog.

In several cases you don't want to hear _all_ tracks of a CD, because only a
few of all tracks are your favorites. For this reason you can use the
@{"programming feature" LINK MaWiProg} of COMPACT. Here you can decide, which tracks you want to
hear and in which order.
When you have a program active, and this entry set to "PROG", the display
for "Total time of CD" will show only the whole program time as the CD-time.
Herewith you can see, how long the total program plays. When you prefer to
always see the total time of the CD (also with active programs), you have to
set this tooltype to "ALL".
@endnode

## -------------------------------

@node "Main_WINDOW" "The main window"
After you have started COMPACT, you will see a window which looks
approximately like this:

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
| @{"*********************************************" LINK MaWiDis1} @{" 1   2   3   4   5   6   7" LINK MaWiDire} |
| * Title time:  00:00 / 00:00   Curr. title: *   8   9  10  11  12  13  14 |
| *             -00:00              00 / 11   *  15  16  17  18  19  +      |
| * 11:40:05                                  *                             |
| *                                 Status:   *  @{"Random" LINK MaWiRand}      @{"Preview" LINK MaWiPrev}       |
| * Total time:  00:00 / 45:20      STOPPED   *                             |
| *             -45:20                        *  @{"Repeat" LINK MaWiRepe}         20          |
| *********************************************                             |
|                                                                           |
| @{"Composer :" LINK MaWiComp}                                                                |
| CD-Name  :                                                                |
| Title    :                                                                |
|                                                                           |
| @{"  STOP  " LINK MaWiStop}  @{"  PLAY  " LINK MaWiPlay}   @{"  PAUSE " LINK MaWiPaus}       @{"Play-Mode" LINK MaWiPlMd}         @{"Proportional" LINK MaWiPrMd}      |
|                                                                           |
| @{"|< SKIP " LINK MaWiSki-}  @{" SKIP >|" LINK MaWiSki+}   @{"  JUMP  " LINK MaWiJump}       * Whole CD        * Whole CD         |
|                                      * Program         * Act. title       |
| @{"< SEARCH" LINK MaWiSea-}  @{"SEARCH >" LINK MaWiSea+}   @{"  EJECT " LINK MaWiEjec}       * Snap-Range      * Program          |
|                                                        * Snap-Range       |
| @{"Program " LINK MaWiProg}  @{" Titles " LINK MaWiTite}                                                       |
|                                                                           |
| 0%               50%              100%       @{"Snap1         Clr" LINK MaWiSnap}            |
| **************************************                                    |
| @{"* I                                  *" LINK MaWiSlid} 0%    Snap2         Clr            |
| **************************************                                    |
|                                                                           |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

You can switch between this window and a very small one by clicking the
zoom gadget in the upper right corner, or by simply pressing TAB.
This small window is created for users who don't have too many place on the
Workbench screen, so they can toggle to this window:

-------------------
| @{"    P L A Y    " LINK MaWiPlay} |
|                 |
| @{" STOP " LINK MaWiStop} @{" PAUSE " LINK MaWiPaus} |
|                 |
| @{"|<" LINK MaWiSki-} @{"<<" LINK MaWiSea-}   @{">>" LINK MaWiSea+} @{">|" LINK MaWiSki+} |
|                 |
| @{"00/01    -00:00" LINK MaWiDis2} |
-------------------

For the most cases you can control the player also by the @{"keyboard" LINK "Main_KEYBOARD"},
which includes the feature that you can control COMPACT from nearly ALL (!)
programs without the need to go to the player's screen and activate its
window! Please read also there to get informations about the online help!
@endnode

@node "MaWiDis1" "The time display"
In this region you can see all the time informations which are necessary to
know about:

@{B}TITLE-TIME:@{UB}
Here you can see how long the actual track is already playing, the total time
of this track and the remaining time to the end of it.

@{B}TOTAL-TIME:@{UB}
Here you can see how long the total CD is already playing, the total time of
the CD and the remaining time to the end of it.
In case of an active program the display depends on your tooltype / menu-
settings: Normally the TOTAL-TIME is based on the length of your active
program, but if you set the config-file-entry @{"TOTALTIME" LINK Tool_TOTTIME} to "NO" or
deactivate the related menuitem "Settings/TotalTime=Prog", then the TOTAL-TIME
is based on the whole CD, like without a program.

@{B}ACTUAL TRACK:@{UB}
The number of the actual track will be displayed here, followed by the total
number of tracks on the CD. When a program is active, or the player is in the
random mode, there will be two lines visible: The first shows you the real
track number and how many tracks are totally on the CD, the second line
displays the current program entry / position of the random order and the
total number of tracks in your program / random order.

@{B}STATUS:@{UB}
Here you can see the current status of COMPACT, and it can be one of the
following:

  - STOPPED	When a "STOP"-command is sent to the drive, or the CD
		reaches its physical end.
  - PLAY	In this case you can hear the music.
  - PAUSE	When in PLAY-mode and you press PAUSE, you will get this one.
  - NO-DISC	In this case no disc is into the drive.
  - DATADISC	When the CD in the drive has no audio tracks, it must be a
		datadisc or similar. Then you can't do any play-commands.

@{B}CLOCK:@{UB}
When activated in the menu or by config-file-entry @{"CLOCK" LINK Tool_CLOCK}, you will see
here the actual time of your computer.


Please note, that all CD-related time displays are calculated from the data
which is stored on the CD, so you can quit the player and start it again, and
the time will be correct. Or if you shake your CD-Rom (you don't should do
this!) and cause it to continue the playing at another place, the time also
will be okay.
@endnode

@node "MaWiDis2" "The time display (small window)"
On the left side the number of the actual track will be displayed, followed by
the total number of tracks on the CD.
On the right side you can see the remaining time of the actual track.
@endnode

@node "MaWiDire" "Direct access to tracks"
There are 19 gadgets for direct access to tracks. Only those which are
available can be used, the others are ghosted. If you insert a CD with no
audio-tracks, all gadgets will be ghosted!
Simply click on it to hear the music of your desired track. If the player
is in the PAUSE mode, you won't hear anything, because only the positioning
will be performed.

With the gadget " + " you can access tracks with a number higher than 19.
When you use it, a window will be opened. Here you can type in your track-
number you want to hear, then click to OKAY or press RETURN. If you want to
cancel this operation, click to the closegadget in the upper left corner of
the window or simply press ESC.
The numbers must contain two digits! To enter your numbers, you can click to
the gadgets ranging from 0 to 9 or use the keyboard. If you have entered a
wrong number, click to "<-" or press DEL or BACKSPACE on the keyboard to
delete the rightmost number.

Please note, that everytime you choose a track with this gadgets, you
select the physical track number! Here a short example:

  Lets say the CD has 4 tracks, and you have a program active with the
  order 3,1,2,4. When you click to the track-gadget "1", you will NOT hear
  the first entry of your program (=physical track 3), but the physical
  track 1 (which is the second entry in your program)!


A second fast method to have direct access to a track is described in the
section about how to use COMPACT with the @{"keyboard" LINK Main_KEYBOARD}!
@endnode

@node "MaWiRand" "Random mode"
When this mode is activated, the sequence of the playback becomes random.
The activation of this mode causes a new shuffle of the sequence, so if the
actual random order is not your matter of taste, simply click on this gadget
twice (which switches the random mode off and afterwards on again) to get a
new sequence of random playback.
Please note that deactivating the random mode will NOT interrupt the actual
playing track, but the activation of this mode will cause a new shuffle and
the start of playback at entry 1 of the new sequence!
The player creates real random sequences at every new shuffle, so the play-
back of the music should nearly never be the same.


When no program is active, you will notice that a second line will appear
under the current title in the time-display, like with an active program.
The first line shows you the REAL tracknumber of the actual playing track,
like it is without the random mode. In the line below you can see the entry
number of the currently playing sequence enclosed in brackets. When playing
the first entry of your random sequence, this number will start with 1.

In case a program is active and you activate the random mode, only all the
tracks in the program are used for the new random sequence! The first line
of the current title in the time-display will show you the REAL tracknumber
of the actual playing track, and the line below enclosed in brackets will
show you the entry number of the actual random order. When you deactivate the
random mode, this second line however stays visible, because it shows you
the entry of your active program-sequence now!

In play-mode "SNAP-RANGE" this mode has no function, because there exists no
sequence which can be shuffled!
@endnode

@node "MaWiPrev" "Preview mode"
When this mode is activated, only the first few seconds of every track will
be played and then a skip to the next track will be performed. The number of
seconds which will be played can be shown in the gadget beside of the preview
gadget, and the default value are 20 seconds. In the same gadget you can
change this value, which must be in the range between 2 and 999. If you type
in a false value you will get an error requester.

In play-mode "SNAP-RANGE" this mode has no function, because there are no
tracks to skip to after the time is up. The snap range will be seen as a
connected block of audio data.
@endnode

@node "MaWiRepe" "Repeat mode"
Normally the player will change to the status "STOPPED" when the CD reaches
its physical end, or if the active program has played its last entry. If you
activate the repeat mode, COMPACT will continue the playback instead of
stopping it.
The playback will never end, as long as your computer runs without system
crashes and the player remains running.

In play-mode "SNAP-RANGE" this mode has no function, because the snap range
already defines the area which is repeated always!
@endnode

@node "MaWiComp" "Composer / CD-Name / Title"
Here you can read the composer, the name of the CD and the name of the actual
playing track of your CD. If no disc is in the drive, nothing will be
displayed.
The first time you insert a CD, you must of course type in this data, because
it is not stored on it. Any other time you listen to this disc, these names
are displayed automatically, as long as you have saved it to disk. The path
to save this data can be controlled by the config-file-entry @{"PATH" LINK Tool_PATH}.
While the program is running you can change it by selecting the
menu "Settings/Save-Load-Path". To enter the names and save it to disk you
have to use the gadget @{"Titles" LINK MaWiTite}.
@endnode

@node "MaWiStop" "S T O P"
As the name says, it stops playing the CD and finishes the drive activity.
The drive will be positioned to the start of the CD.
@endnode

@node "MaWiPlay" "P L A Y"
This command has several functions which depends on the current status of
the player:

Status @{B}STOPPED@{UB}:	  In this case the player will start to play with the first
		  audio track of your CD. When a program is active, the first
		  entry of it will be played.
Status @{B}PAUSED@{UB}:	  Here the player continues to play the audio data.
Status @{B}PLAY@{UB}:	  Herewith you can restart the actual track at its beginning.
@endnode

@node "MaWiPaus" "P A U S E"
This command has several functions which depends on the current status of
the player:

Status @{B}PLAY@{UB}:	The drive suspends the playback of your CD and waits.
		After the status changed to "PAUSED", all commands which
		normally would play music will now only perform positioning
		without starting to play. This affects the following
		commands:
		SKIP FORWARDS, SKIP BACKWARDS, SEARCH FORWARDS, SEARCH BACK-
		WARDS, JUMP, PROPORTIONAL-SLIDER, BOOKMARK

Status @{B}PAUSE@{UB}:	When pressed while the status is set to "PAUSED", the player
		will continue to play the music at the place the drive is
		currently positioned (see notes above).
@endnode

@node "MaWiSki-" "S K I P   B A C K W A R D S"
You can skip to the track before the actual playing one by using this
command. The player then will start playing at the beginning of the new
track, except the player is just paused.
When in pause-mode, only the positioning will be performed, and there exists
two possibilities:

  @{B}1. The actual paused track has played at least 1 second:@{UB}
     In this case a skip backwards will go to the start of the current
     track, and then the player stays in the pause-mode.

  @{B}2. The actual paused track is at its start (like after the example above):@{UB}
     In this case a skip backwards will go to the start of the previous
     track, and then the player stays in the pause-mode.


When a program is active, skipping forwards or backwards is based on the
sequence of your program and not on the physical sequence of your tracks.
@endnode

@node "MaWiSki+" "S K I P   F O R W A R D S"
You can skip to the track after the actual playing one by using this
command. The player then will start playing at the beginning of the new
track, except the player is just paused. When in pause-mode, only the
positioning will be performed, which goes to the start of the next track,
and then the player stays in the pause-mode.

When a program is active, skipping forwards or backwards is based on the
sequence of your program and not on the physical sequence of your tracks.
@endnode

@node "MaWiJump" "J U M P"
With this gadget you can jump to any location on the CD immediately. When you
activate the gadget, a window will be opened. Here you can type in the
minutes and seconds of the location you want to start the playback, then
click OKAY or press RETURN to jump to the new position. If you want to cancel
this operation, click to the closegadget in the upper left corner of
the window or simply press ESC.

When the position is in a valid range, COMPACT starts to play at this place
immediately, but when you enter an invalid position nothing will happen. If
the player is paused, only the position will be changed and no playback will
be started.

You must enter four digits, the first two for the minutes and the last two
for the seconds. To enter your numbers, you can click to the gadgets ranging
from 0 to 9 or use the keyboard. If you have entered a wrong number, click
to "<-" or press DEL or BACKSPACE on the keyboard to delete the rightmost
number.
Please note, that when entering the first digit of the seconds, you can not
use numbers higher than 5, because a minute has a maximum of 59 seconds!

When the player is in the random mode or you have activated a program or a
snap-range, this gadget has no function because you could jump to a position
which is not included in your program / snap-range!
@endnode

@node "MaWiSea-" "S E A R C H   B A C K W A R D S"
This command continues the playback of your CD at a few seconds before the
current position. You can change the number of seconds via the menu
@{"Settings/SEARCHSECONDS" LINK m2sear}. By default the difference are 10 seconds. This
number is saved in the config-file, when you select "Save configuration" in
the menu "Settings".

Please note, that you can go behind the beginning of the actual playing
track, as long as it is not the first one. This doesn't works when a program
is active!
@endnode

@node "MaWiSea+" "S E A R C H   F O R W A R D S"
This command continues the playback of your CD at a few seconds after the
current position. You can change the number of seconds via the menu
@{"Settings/SEARCHSECONDS" LINK m2sear}. By default the difference are 10 seconds. This
number is saved in the config-file, when you select "Save configuration" in
the menu "Settings".

Please note, that you can go behind the end of the actual playing track,
as long as it is not the last one. This doesn't works when a program is
active!
@endnode

@node "MaWiEjec" "E J E C T"
Herewith you can open / close the drawer of your drive, as long as it is
supported by the drive itself. In a few circumstances it could be that the
drive does not react on this command. In this case you must open / close the
drive by yourself, but this will appear very rarely. On the Overdrive-CDRom
for example this effect appears, when the drawer has not been opened since
turning on the Amiga. After you opened the drawer once manually, the eject-
function should work fine all the time.

There exists the option @{"EJECTOVERDRIVE" LINK Tool_EJECT} in the config-file, which normally is
set to "NO".
You need this one for a few drives which don't recognize the standard SCSI-
command for ejecting the CD, like for example the Archos Overdrive. When your
drive doesn't reacts correctly you can try to change it via the menu
"Settings/Overdrive-EJECT". When you select "Save configuration" in the menu
"Settings", the choosen mode can be saved.
@endnode

@node "MaWiProg" "Controlling the program"
When you use the gadget "program" in the main window, a new window for
controlling the program will appear. A program means that you can define
a new sequence of playing the tracks of your CD, you can play a track more
than once, you can leave out tracks you don't want to hear, etc.
When you enter this window and a track is playing currently, this track
will be highlighted at the list of all available tracks.

You can create up to 99 entrys for your program. To do this, you can click
into the left list of the tracks, in which you can see all available tracks
of the actual CD. After the click the track will be appended to the end of
the right list, which displays all tracks in the currently defined program.
If there are more tracks in a list than the list can display, you can use
the sliders at their right side to scroll through the list up and down.
Under the right list you can see the sum of the time of all tracks in the
currently defined program.

Also there are gadgets between the two lists. All these gadgets will perform
a function to the list of your actual program (at the right side)! These
gadgets have the following functions:

	@{"---COPY-->" LINK ProgCopy}
	@{"Clear all " LINK ProgClea}
	@{"Delete    " LINK ProgDele}

	@{"Viewmode  " LINK ProgView}

	@{"First / Last / Up / Down" LINK ProgFirst}
	@{"RND" LINK ProgRND}      @{"REV" LINK ProgREV}

At the bottom of the window there are gadgets for saving/loading a program,
and for use or cancel the actual program. These gadgets have the following
functions:

	@{"Save     " LINK ProgSave}
	@{"Save Def." LINK ProgSaveDef}
	@{"Load     " LINK ProgLoad}
	@{"Load Def." LINK ProgLoadDef}

	@{"Use      " LINK ProgUse}
	@{"Cancel   " LINK ProgCancel}

@{B}Please note:@{UB}  When a program is active and you open this window to define a
new program, the currently playing program stays valid as long as you click
to "USE" in the window! When you click to "CANCEL" or use the close-gadget
of the window, the old currently playing program is still valid and
unchanged!
@endnode
@node "MaWiTite" "Changing the name of CD / Composer / Tracks"
When you press this button, a new window will appear. Here you can type in and
edit the titles of all tracks, the composer of the CD and the name of the CD.
The data you type in will be stored to the path which can be defined by the
config-file entry @{"PATH" LINK Tool_PATH}. You also can change the path while the player
is running, by selecting the menu "@{"Settings/Save-Load-Path" LINK m2path}".
The filename which will be used for saving is the @{"ID-number" LINK IDnumber}, which is
calculated by the player.

@{B}The following gadgets are available for recording the data mentioned above:@{UB}

	@{"Composer" LINK NameComp}
	@{"CD-Name " LINK NameCDNa}
	@{"Year    " LINK NameYear}	@{"Recording technology" LINK NameTech}
	@{"Comment " LINK NameComm}

	@{"Del    " LINK NameDel}	@{"Ins    " LINK NameIns}
	@{"Save   " LINK NameSave}	@{"Re-Load" LINK NameLoad}

	@{"Category of the CD" LINK NameCate}
	@{"Edit-Mode         " LINK NameEdMd}

	@{"With Bookmarks" LINK NameBkSv}

(When you opened this window from the @{U}database@{UU} (with the EDIT button), then
you will see these @{"additional buttons" LINK MaWiEditAdd} too.)

Also you can see a big area for the titles of all tracks. When no titles are
defined for the tracks, you can see here the track numbers. When you click to
an entry of this list, you can edit the contents in the string-gadget below
this listview gadget. Please note, that it depends on the status of the
"Edit-Mode"-gadget, whether a blank line will appear into the string gadget
or the contents of the list are copied into it!
When you click to an entry of the list, the track number of it will appear
on the left side of the string gadget.

When you press ENTER or TAB to store the actual track name, the next entry in
the list will be copied to the string gadget, as long as the actual track was
not the last one. With TAB you can move forwards through all string gadgets,
with Shift-TAB this can be done backwards.

All the data you store to disk can be used into the database.
@endnode

@node "MaWiPlMd" "Changing the playmode"
You can set the playmode to one of the following:

  - @{B}Whole CD@{UB}

    In this mode the whole CD will be played, and the tracks will be played
    in the physical order of the CD, as long as the random mode is not
    activated.
    This playmode enables the modes "Whole CD" and "Act. title" for the
    @{"Proportional mode" LINK MaWiPrMd}.
    When you eject the CD this mode will be automatically activated.

    Switching from a program or a snap-range to this playmode doesn't cause
    a track re-start, but it continues to play at the current play-position.
    This however is not valid when the random mode is active, because a new
    random order will be created every time when changing the playmode!

  - @{B}Program@{UB}

    This mode can only be activated, when you have defined a @{"program" LINK MaWiProg} with
    at least 1 track, and confirmed it by clicking to USE in the program-
    control window. When you delete all program-entrys and click to USE,
    the playmode will be automatically changed to "Whole CD".
    This playmode enables the modes "Act. title" and "Program" for the
    @{"Proportional mode" LINK MaWiPrMd}.

    When you switch to this playmode, and the actual playing track is inside
    the program, no track re-start will be performed and COMPACT continues
    to play at the current play-position. This however is not valid when the
    random mode is active, because a new random order will be created every
    time when changing the playmode!

  - @{B}Snap-Range@{UB}

    This mode can only be activated, when the two snap-points are set
    correctly by using the two @{"SNAP" LINK MaWiSnap} gadgets. The player will start to play
    from the position set by "Snap 1" until it reaches the position defined
    by "Snap 2". At this point COMPACT jumps back to the "Snap 1"-position
    and continues to play until it reaches snap 2 again (and so on).
    This playmode enables the modes "Whole CD" and "Snap-Range" for the
    @{"Proportional mode" LINK MaWiPrMd}.

    When you switch to this playmode, and the actual playing track is inside
    the snap-range, no track re-start will be performed and COMPACT
    continues to play at the current play-position.

    In this mode the three modes "Random", "Repeat" and "Preview" have no
    function, because the snap-range will be continuously played forever.
@endnode

@node "MaWiPrMd" "Changing the mode of the proportional slider"
With this pair of gadgets you can set the base for the @{"proportional slider" LINK MaWiSlid}.
You can set the proportional mode to one of the following:

  - @{B}Whole CD@{UB}

    With this mode the length of the slider represents the length of the
    whole CD, and the current slider-position is the actual playing position.
    When the slider-position is at 0% the player is at the start of the CD,
    at 50% it is in the middle of the CD, etc.
    It can't be activated when the @{"playmode" LINK MaWiPlMd} is set to "Program".

  - @{B}Act. title@{UB}

    When you activate this mode, the length of the slider represents the
    length of the actual playing track, and the current slider-position is
    the relative position within this track. When it is at 0% the player is
    at the start of the title, at 50% it is in the middle of this title, etc.
    It can't be activated when the @{"playmode" LINK MaWiPlMd} is set to "Snap-Range".

  - @{B}Program@{UB}

    With this one activated the length of the slider represents the length
    of your currently running program, so if you change it, the relative
    position of the slider-position will change appropriate too!
    When the slider-position is at 0% the player is at the start of your
    program, at 50% it is in the middle of the program, etc.
    It can't be activated when the @{"playmode" LINK MaWiPlMd} is set to "Whole CD" or
    to "Snap-Range".

  - @{B}Snap-Range@{UB}

    With this mode the length of the slider represents the length of the
    currently playing snap-range, and the current slider-position is the
    relative position within this one. When it is at 0% the player is at the
    start of the snap-range, at 50% it is in the middle of the range, etc.
    It can't be activated when the @{"playmode" LINK MaWiPlMd} is set to "Whole CD" or
    to "Program".

    Please note: When you define a very short snap-range (like for example
    two seconds or so), you can't see every position of the range correctly
    in the slider, because it's display is updated only every second!
@endnode

@node "MaWiSlid" "The proportional slider"
The proportional slider is dependent on the currently used @{"proportional mode" LINK MaWiPrMd}.
For example, if the proportional mode is set to "Whole CD", the length of the
slider represents the length of the whole CD. While the CD is playing, the
actual slider-position will be updated every second, so you can see the
relative position (in percent) to the base the proportional mode is set to.

The slider has two functions:

  @{B}1. It displays the position in dependence of the proportional mode.@{UB}

  @{B}2. You can jump to every position by moving the slider.@{UB}

     This can be done by simply clicking to the slider and holding down the
     left mouse button. Now you can move it to the relative position and then
     release the mouse button. This causes the player to continue the play-
     back at the new position.

     @{U}For example:@{UU}

     The proportional-mode is set to "Act. title" and you want to jump to the
     last quarter of this track. Move the mouse over the slider, click with
     the left mouse and hold it down. Now drag the slider to the position at
     75% and release the button. The player will continue to play at the last
     quarter of the actual track.
@endnode

@node "MaWiSnap" "Set / Clear the two snaps"
There exists two gadgets to set both points for the snaps: "SNAP 1" and
"SNAP 2". Click on the gadgets to set it to the actual physical playing time
of the whole CD. When both snaps are set, you have defined the snap-range,
which then can be activated by setting the @{"Playmode" LINK MaWiPlMd} to Snap-Range.
Please note, that you can not set Snap1 behind the time of Snap2, because
the snap-range is always from Snap1 to Snap2, so Snap1 must be before Snap2!

When you want to overwrite an existing snap point, you can simply click to
the Snap gadget again and the actual time will be set (as long as Snap1 is
before Snap2; see above). This only works when the play-mode is not set to
"Snap-Range".

To clear a snap-point, you can click to the gadget "CLR" at the right side
of the place where the time of the snap-point is displayed. This also works
only when the play-mode is not set to "Snap-Range".
@endnode

@node "MaWiEditAdd" "Additional buttons for EDIT from database"

SNAP1:		Here you can change the two snap points, which can be saved
SNAP2:		with the ID-file. If you type in nothing or wrong characters,
		it will be treated as empty, which is displayed as "-----".

BOOKMARK:	Here you can change the 10 bookmarks, which can also be
		saved with the file. To select one of the bookmarks, you
		can use the slider. After this you can change the value in
		the gadget below. If you type in nothing or wrong characters,
		it will be treated as empty, which is displayed as "-----".

Please note, that your bookmarks and snap points will only be saved to the
ID-file, if the button @{"With Bookmarks" LINK NameBkSv} is activated!
@endnode

## **************  PROG  ***************

@node "ProgCopy" "---COPY-->    Copy all available tracks into program list"
When you press this button, all available tracks of your actual CD will be
copied to the program list. You will have an exact copy of the original
sequence, but you can of course change it like you want.
@endnode
@node "ProgClea" "Clear         Clear all entries in the program list"
This function clears all entries of the program, so it will be empty!
Because there is no program available after this step, the two SAVE-gadgets
will be ghosted!
@endnode
@node "ProgDele" "Delete        Delete actual selected program entry"
To use this function you must first select an entry in the program list.
After you press this button, this entry will be deleted and all program
entries below the deleted one will jump one position higher.
The selection in the program list stays available, so if you click this
button for example three times, the three entries at the current position
will be deleted.

When the program list is empty after pressing this button, the two SAVE-
gadgets will be ghosted, because there is no program available to save!
@endnode
@node "ProgView" "Viewmode      Change between two viewmodes"
With this button you can toggle between two modes of how the tracks in both
lists will be displayed:

@{B}Viewmode TITLES:@{UB}

Here all tracks are displayed with their names. When the names are not
available, because you haven't typed it in by using the gadget @{"Titles" LINK MaWiTite} in
the main window, the track numbers will be displayed.

@{B}Viewmode NUMBERS:@{UB}

Here all tracks are displayed with their track number, regardless whether
you typed in the names of the tracks or not.
@endnode
@node "ProgFirst" "First / Last / Up / Down"
You first must select an entry in the program list, then you can use one of
the following gadgets:

@{B}FIRST:@{UB}

The selected entry will be moved to the top position of the list.

@{B}LAST:@{UB}

The selected entry will be moved to the bottom position of the list.

@{B}UP:@{UB}

The selected entry will be moved one position higher, so the entry above
will move below the selected one.

@{B}DOWN:@{UB}

The selected entry will be moved one position lower, so the entry below
will move above the selected one.
@endnode
@node "ProgRND" "RND           Shuffle your currently edited program in a random order"
When you press this button, the sequence of your program in the right list
will be shuffled in a random order. Everytime you click to it, a new random
sequence will be created.
Please note, that you need at least 2 entries for this function!
@endnode
@node "ProgREV" "REV           Reverse the sequence of your program"
With this function you can reverse your program. The first entry will be the
last, and the last one will be the first. Please note, that you need at
least 2 entries for this function!
@endnode
@node "ProgSave" "Save          Save program to file"
When you use this button, a filerequester will appear and you can define the
path and the name of the file, in which the actual defined program will be
saved. If you don't want to save your program, you can click to the Cancel-
gadget in the filerequester.
@endnode
@node "ProgLoad" "Load          Load a saved program"
With this function you can load a previously saved program into the program
list. The currently defined program will be overwritten!


@{U}There exists a problem with this function. A short example will explain it:@{UU}

Lets say you have a CD in your drive which contains 10 tracks, and you
define a program for it, which contains all 10 tracks, only in an other
sequence, like this:  3,9,1,7,4,2,6,5,10,8
Now you save this program to a file and after that you click to "USE" in the
program window.
Now you eject the CD and insert an other one which contains only 6 tracks.
You open the program window and because you don't want to create a new
program, you decide to load a previously saved one. You click to "LOAD" and
choose the same file you saved in the example above.
The problem which occurs is the fact, that your actual CD only has 6 tracks,
in the saved file however are 10 tracks. The player now ignores all tracks
which are higher than the maximum tracks of the actual CD, so the result you
get after loading this program will be:  3,1,4,2,6,5
@endnode
@node "ProgSaveDef" "SaveDef       Save a default program"
Your actual defined program will be saved to disk, but in this case you
don't need to define a filename! The principle which is used here is the same
as by saving the CD name and the titles of the tracks: COMPACT creates an
unique @{"ID-number" LINK IDnumber} and saves it to the same path where your titles are saved.

All program files will get the prefix "PR" before their ID, so the name
"PR14770605390525" for example will be a valid filename.


Well, how can you use these files? The idea behind this procedure is, that in
many cases you have a few tracks on every CD, which you don't like, and other
titles, which you like very much. So you can create a program with your
favorite titles and save it as the default program of this CD. Everytime when
you insert this CD into the drive, COMPACT creates the ID-number of the CD
and tries to load the corresponding default program. If it is available, you
only need to switch the @{"playmode" LINK MaWiPlMd} to "Program", and COMPACT is ready to play
the tracks you like so much.

A default program can also be used by using the feature of COMPACT to start
the playback immediately after being started. This can be defined via the
menu "@{"Settings / PLAY after start" LINK m2plst}", and it will be saved to the config-file
too. If a default program exists for the actual CD and the entry LOADDEFPROG
is set to YES (via menu "@{"Settings / Load default prog." LINK m2defp}"), the player will
use the default program automatically after being started.
@endnode
@node "ProgLoadDef" "LoadDef       Load a default program"
Normally you will not need this function, because a default program is read
automatically when the CD is inserted. But when you subsequently change or
delete the program list, and you want to get the original default program,
you can use this button.
At the description of the gadget @{"Save Def" LINK ProgSaveDef} you can read what a default
program can be used for.
@endnode
@node "ProgUse" "Use           Use the defined program in the player"
With this gadget you transfer the defined program from the program window to
the player. If you don't want to do this, but the currently active program
should stay valid, you must use the "CANCEL" button or click to the window's
close gadget.

After pressing this button, the program window will be closed.
@endnode
@node "ProgCancel" "Cancel        Don't change anything"
With this button you can close the program window, and all changes will be
lost! You can do the same by clicking the close-gadget of the window or by
pressing ESC.
@endnode

@node "IDnumber" "The unique ID-number"
The following example describes how the ID-number is built:

Lets say your ID-number is "14770605390525". This number means (from left
to right): The CD has 14 tracks, the total playing time of the CD is 77:06,
the playing time of the first track is 05:39, the playing time of the
second track is 05:25.
When the CD has only one track, the time for track two in the ID-number will
be defined to be 00:00, and the playing time of track one and the whole
playing time of the CD should be the same.

When default programs are saved, the prefix "PR" will be put before the ID,
the prefix "ID" will be used when saving titles.

In this way a CD can be recognized with a highly probability, and it should
not appear, that two or more CDs will produce the same ID-number.
@endnode


## **************  TITLE  ***************

@node "NameComp" "Entering the composer of the CD"
Here you can enter the composer of the CD. You can use up to 55 characters.
After you entered it, the composer name will be updated at all relevant
places where it appears (like for example in the main window).
@endnode
@node "NameCDNa" "Entering the title of the CD"
Here you can enter the name of the CD. You can use up to 55 characters.
After you entered it, the CD-name will be updated at all relevant places
where it appears (like for example in the main window).
@endnode
@node "NameYear" "Entering the year of the CD"
Here you can enter the creation year of the CD. Please use 4 numbers, like
for example 1996. If you don't follow this rule, it can cause wrong results
in the database, because an entry of "96" will be lower than "1995", so you
can't compare years into the database with "<", ">" etc.
@endnode
@node "NameTech" "Entering the recording technology of the CD"
The Compact Disc's superior performance is the result of laser-optical
scanning combined with digital playback, and is independent of the technology
used in making the original recording.
This recording technology is identified on the back cover by a three-letter
code:

@{B}DDD@{UB}	Digital tape recorder used during session recording, mixing
	and/or editing, and mastering (transcription).
@{B}ADD@{UB}	Analogue tape recorder used during session recording; digital
	tape recorder used during subsequent mixing and/or editing and during
	mastering (transcription).
@{B}AAD@{UB}	Analogue tape recorder used during session recording and
	subsequent mixing and/or editing; digital tape recorder used during
	mastering (transcription).

If you know what technology is used by the CD, you can click to this gadget
as long as the correct code appears, otherwise you can leave it to the
default entry "---", which means that the recording technology is unknown.
@endnode
@node "NameComm" "Entering a private comment to this CD"
You can enter a private comment to the actual CD, which will be stored with
the other data. You can read the comment of the CD by selecting "CD-Info"
in the menu "Project". Also you can access the comments to CDs into the
database. You can use upto 150 characters for your comment.
@endnode
@node "NameDel" "Delete the actual choosen entry of the list"
With this button you can delete the actual choosen entry of the list, and an
empty line will be created at the bottom of it.
@endnode
@node "NameIns" "Inserting an empty line into the list"
With this button you can insert an empty line at the highlighted position in
the list. The last entry in the list will be discarded.
@endnode
@node "NameSave" "Save all entered titles to disk"
Saves all data of this window to disk. The filename which is used hereby is
built by the program itself, using an unique @{"ident number" LINK "IDnumber"}.
So everytime you insert this CD again, this file will be loaded immediately
and the stored data will be available to the program.

When the gadget "With Bookmarks" is active, the 10 bookmarks of the menu
"Special" and the two snap points of the snap-range are saved to the file too.
So every time a CD is inserted or COMPACT is started (and only there), these
bookmarks and snap points are loaded and can be used again. You can use this
for example, to mark positions on a CD, which you must often jump to.

After saving is finished, the window will be closed.
@endnode
@node "NameBkSv" "With Bookmarks"
If this gadget is activated, the 10 bookmarks defined in the menu "Special"
and the two snap points of the snap-range will be saved to the ID-file too.
Also they will be reloaded, when you press the button "Re-Load".

(If you opened this window from the database with the EDIT-button, the
bookmarks and snap points will be used from the editor window.)

Every time a CD is inserted or COMPACT is started (and only there), these
bookmarks and snap points are loaded and can be used again. You can use this
for example, to mark positions on a CD, which you must often jump to.

If the gadget isn't activated, the bookmarks and the snap points aren't
included in the ID-file (when saving), and they aren't loaded (when Re-
Loading).
To delete the bookmark-information in the file, you can set this gadget to
inactive (not checked), and save the file again.

The compatibility between older versions of COMPACT and newer files is given,
so older versions of the player can load newer files (with bookmarks) without
problems, and newer versions of COMPACT can load older files (without book-
marks).
@endnode
@node "NameLoad" "Re-Load the actual titles from disk"
With this button you can re-load the data to the actual CD. This is needed,
when you made changes in the window and want to return to the original data.

When the gadget "With Bookmarks" is active, the 10 bookmarks of the menu
"Special" and the two snap points of the snap-range are reloaded from the
file too.
@endnode
@node "NameCate" "Choose the category of the CD"
One of the following category can be selected for the CD:

  SINGER	A single person is associated with the composer's name
  GROUP		Several people are associated with the composer's name
  SAMPLER	The CD has different composers
  MAXI		The CD is a Maxi-CD
  SOUNDTRACK	The CD is the soundtrack to a movie

This category can be used as a filter into the database.
@endnode
@node "NameEdMd" "Choose the edit mode for the list of all tracks"
You can choose between two modes for the list-edit:

@{B}Normal:@{UB}

When you click at an entry of the title-list, it's content will be copied to
the string-gadget at the bottom of the list, where you can edit it.

@{B}Blank:@{UB}

When this mode is active, an empty line will be created at the string-gadget.
This for example is useful, if you don't want to delete the numbers of every
line manually at the first time you enter names for a CD.
@endnode

## -------------------------------

@node "Main_KEYBOARD" "Using the player with the keyboard"
Many function of the player can be controlled by the keyboard, as long as the
window of COMPACT is active. In many cases a character of the gadget-text is
underlined, which means that you can press this underlined character to per-
form the same thing as clicking to the gadget. In addition there exists also
other keys with no underlined character in the gadget visible.

@{B}KEYS WITHOUT GADGETS:@{UB}

- Everytime you want to close a window, you can either click to the close-
  gadget in the upper left corner, or use the ESC-key. When you do this
  while the main window is the active one, the player will quit.

- A fast method to have direct access to a track is the following:
  You can type the two (!) digits of your track number and the jump will be
  performed immediately after pressing the second number. The time between
  the first and the second digit must not be greater than 4 seconds,
  otherwise the first one will be deleted.
  Your input can be shown at the right side of the " + "-gadget, which is
  cleared after the 4 seconds or when the two digits are entered. If COMPACT
  runs on its own custom screen, you can show your input at the right side of
  the actual track number.

- When the player runs on a public screen like for example the Workbench, it
  can be used with two main windows: the big one you see at startup and a
  small version. You can toggle between these windows by clicking to the zoom
  gadget in the upper right corner of the window or by pressing TAB on your
  keyboard.
  When the player runs on its own custom screen, the key TAB toggles the
  colour cycling effect on / off, as long as the background picture has
  more than 4 colours. There exists also an extra window for working with
  colours, when COMPACT runs on an own custom screen!

- When a menu item has at its right side the image of the Amiga key and a
  following character, you can press the right Amiga key and this character
  together to perform the same action as selecting this menu item via the
  mouse.


@{B}KEYS CONCERNING THE ONLINE-HELP:@{UB}

- While moving the mouse through an active window of COMPACT, you will see
  a short explanation to the gadget under the mouse at the screen title bar,
  when you stop the movement of the mouse.
  If you want more detailed informations to this gadget, simply press the
  HELP key, and the AmigaGuide document will be opened at the part
  concerning this gadget.

  When you move through the menus of the player, you can get help to the
  current selected menu item by pressing the HELP key! In this case the
  AmigaGuide document will be opened at the part concerning this menu item.


@{B}KEYS WHICH CAN BE USED FROM NEARLY EVERY OTHER PROGRAM:@{UB}

- You can control COMPACT from nearly every program which supports multi-
  tasking without the need to activate the window of the player! You can
  press several @{"hotkey combinations" LINK Tool_HOT} to send your commands to COMPACT, inde-
  pendent of the fact whether you are working on an other screen/window
  or not.
  Please note, that this doesn't work, as long as a file-requester or a
  requester the user must respond is opened from the player!


@{B}KEYS WHICH BELONGS TO GADGETS WITHOUT AN UNDERLINED CHARACTER:@{UB}

There are several keys available for the functions SKIP and SEARCH:

  Command		Possible keys
  ===================================================
  SKIP FORWARDS:	<+>,  <]>,  <Arrow right>
  SKIP BACKWARDS:	<->,  <[>,  <Arrow left>
  SEARCH FORWARDS:	<*>,  <\\>,  <Arrow up>
  SEARCH BACKWARDS:	<_>,  </>,  <Arrow down>,  <=>

The Arrow-keys can be used independent whether the main window is the
active one or an other.
@endnode

## -------------------------------

