    @{"Use Book-mark" LINK m3useb}
    @{"PubScreen-Jump" LINK m3pubs}

@endnode

@node "m1abou" "Menu:  Project / About"
Tells you the version number of COMPACT and informations about the name of
the ARexx port, the name of the public screen and the main hotkey.
Also you can see, how long COMPACT is already running and how many discs
were in the drive since the start of it.
@endnode
@node "m1cdin" "Menu:  Project / CD-Info"
Shows you the number of tracks for the actual CD, the total playing time and
the ID-number. Also you can read here the comment to this CD, as long as
it is available.

Additionally you can read here, how often you heard the actual CD, and at
which date you heard it the first and the last time. These informations are
only displayed with Audio-CDs, not with Data-CDs.
@endnode
@node "m1regi" "Menu:  Project / Registration"
When you are registrated, which means, you payed the shareware fee and
received your keyfile, you can read here your name and address and the
serial number.
When you are not registrated, you will be told that you are using the
demo version of COMPACT.
@endnode
@node "m1devi" "Menu:  Project / Set Device"
Opens a window in which you can select the device and the device number to
use in the player. The unit number can be selected via the three slider bars
or you can type in the number manually.
Please note, that this setting is only valid since COMPACT is running! To
store your device-settings, you must edit the tooltypes of the player's icon.
@endnode
@node "m1hide" "Menu:  Project / Hide"
Hides the player, so you will not see it anymore. When selected, a appicon
will appear at the Workbench (see tooltype @{"APPICON" LINK Tool_APPICON}).
When you start COMPACT again while it is still running, the new started
task will quit immediately and the hidden task of COMPACT will open its
window again.
@endnode
@node "m1quit" "Menu:  Project / Quit"
This quits the player and frees all memory etc. it has allocated. You also
can quit by pressing ESC in the main window or click to the closegadget at
the player's main window. When COMPACT was started from a shell, you can
also send a CTRL-C to quit the player.
Eventually a "STOP"-command will be sent to the drive before the program
ends (see the menu @{"'STOP' before quit" LINK m2stqu}).
@endnode
@node "m2cloc" "Menu:  Settings / Clock in display"
When active, the actual time of your computer will be visible in the
display for the CD-time.
@endnode
@node "m2ejec" "Menu:  Settings / Overdrive-Eject"
When active, the eject-command for the Overdrive CD-ROM will be used, other-
wise the normal SCSI-command will be used.
See @{"Configfile entry EJECTOVERDRIVE" LINK Tool_EJECT}.
@endnode
@node "m2file" "Menu:  Settings / Save with filenote"
When active, your ID files will be saved with a filenote.
See @{"Configfile entry FILENOTE" LINK Tool_FILENOTE}.
@endnode
@node "m2defp" "Menu:  Settings / Load default program"
When active, default programs are loaded immediately.
See @{"Configfile entry LOADDEFPROG" LINK Tool_LOADDEFPRG}.
@endnode
@node "m2stqu" "Menu:  Settings / 'STOP' before quit"
When active, a STOP-command will be sent to the drive before the program
finishes its work.
@endnode
@node "m2plst" "Menu:  Settings / 'PLAY' after start"
When active, the player will start immediately after being started.
See @{"Configfile entry PLAYSTART" LINK Tool_PLAYSTART}.
@endnode
@node "m2totp" "Menu:  Settings / TotalTime = Prog"
When active, the display of the total time of the actual CD will be the
sum of the actual program (when a program exits). Otherwise it will be
the total time of the physical length of the CD.
See @{"Configfile entry TOTALTIME" LINK Tool_TOTTIME}.
@endnode
@node "m2ever" "Menu:  Settings / Start at every track"
When active, an extra play command will be sent to the drive after every
new track. You probably will never need this option!
See @{"Configfile entry STARTEVERYTRACK" LINK Tool_STARTET}.
@endnode
@node "m2full" "Menu:  Settings / Full palette"
When active, the full palette including colour numbers 0 to 3 are used when
loading a background picture for your own screen. The drawback is, that the
gadgets (and/or the menu) probably will not be visible anymore, when the
first colours of your picture have nearly the same colour. Therefore this
menu has the shortcut RightAmiga-f, so when you loaded a picture and all
gadgets are not visible anymore, press this shortcut and the first 4 colours
are set to its default values.
This option can also be needful when loading HAM pictures.

See @{"Configfile entry FULLPALETTE" LINK Tool_FULLPAL}.
@endnode
@node "m2titl" "Menu:  Settings / Show screen title bar"
When active, the screen title bar is visible on your own screen, otherwise
it will be invisible. Has no effect when working on a public screen like the
Workbench!
On your own custom screen you only can read the gadget-help, when the screen
bar is visible. To drag the screen or put it to the background, there is
always a 1-pixel-line at the top of the screen available, and the screen has
the autoscroll-feature enabled!
@endnode
@node "m2t10s" "Menu:  Settings / Save TOP10 immediately"
This switch decides, whether or not the TOP10 file will be saved immediately
after a change in the memory. When it isn't active, the TOP10 file will
be saved only, when you quit COMPACT.
In the memory, the data about the TOP10 is always actual; this switch
only is for controlling the behavior of the save routine.

More informations about the TOP10 feature can be read in the section about
the @{"statistic window" LINK Statisti}.


@{U}@{B}Please keep in mind the following:@{UB}@{UU}

When you switch this menu entry from inactiv to active, the TOP10 data will
be saved immediately once. This is be done, because when you made changes
to TOP10 data while "Save TOP10 immediately" isn't active, and then you
set it to active, and THEN you quit COMPACT, the TOP10 data wouldn't be
saved. Therefore it will be saved after setting this menu entry to active.


See @{"Configfile entry TOP10SAVEONCE" LINK Tool_TOP10SAVEONCE}.
@endnode
@node "m2prio" "Menu:  Settings / Taskpriority"
Here you can set the task priority of COMPACT to -1, 0 or +1.
See @{"Configfile entry TASKPRI" LINK Tool_TASKPRI}.
@endnode
@node "m2path" "Menu:  Settings / Save-/Load-path..."
Here you can set the path for storing the ID-files.
See @{"Configfile entry PATH" LINK Tool_PATH}.
@endnode
@node "m2sear" "Menu:  Settings / SEARCH-Seconds..."
Here you can define, how many seconds are used when pressing a SEARCH-button.
See @{"Configfile entry SEARCHSECS" LINK Tool_SEARCHSEC}.
@endnode
@node "m2save" "Menu:  Settings / Save configuration..."
With this menu you can save all settings to the config-file, so at every
start of COMPACT your settings will be like you defined it. A requester
will open and you can choose between three options:

- @{B}INCLUDE ALL WINDOW-POSITIONS@{UB}
  All your settings will be saved to the config-file, and in addition to
  this all current positions of your windows (and partly the dimensions
  of it). When a window was never opened since the start of COMPACT, the
  position will be set to -1, which means, that at the first opening the
  default position will be used. If a window is closed while using this
  menu, its positions will be used nevertheless.

  In addition to the positions of the windows, the info whether they are
  opened or closed will be saved. When COMPACT starts, this status will be
  restored. This will be done for the following windows:
    - Main window (including the info, whether the main window is the normal
      gui, the small gui, an own custom screen or in hidden mode)
    - Own Tracklist window
    - Own window for names
    - Database

- @{B}INCLUDE ONLY THE SETTINGS@{UB}
  Only the settings defined in the menu are stored in the config-file. All
  windows will be opened at their default positions after the next start
  of COMPACT.

- @{B}CANCEL@{UB}
  Nothing will be stored.
@endnode

@node "m3scre" "Menu:  Special / Own screen"
With this menu you can switch between the two main display modes in COMPACT.
Normally, COMPACT uses a window on a public screen, like the Workbench. The
other mode uses an own custom screen. On this screen there are the same
gadgets and displays like in the window mode, but at a little bit different
positions.

At the unused screen areas you can display a background IFF picture of your
choice. It can be defined in the config-file with the keyword "@{"IFFNAME" LINK Tool_IFFNAME}", but
you can change the picture while the player is running by using the menu
"@{"Special / Change IFF-picture" LINK m3iffp}". Please read also there for informations about
what happens, when you select a wrong file (for example when the file is not
an IFF picture or not a picture at all, or it has too many colours etc.)!
Please note, that you need the iff.library for loading pictures. It will be
installed by the Installer script automatically. Because this library supports
the XPK compression library, you can compress your pictures with XPK and
load it as your background pictures with no difference to normal pictures!

The first line at the top of the screen is the dragbar, so you can scroll
the screen down to see the screen behind it. Also you can use the (invisible)
depth-gadget at the right side of this first line, to put the screen behind
all other opened screens. The screen also has the autoscroll feature enabled,
so you can click to an unused area of the screen to activate it, and then you
can move the mouse to the bottom of your monitor to scroll the screen up.

If you prefer to see the normal screen bar, you can use the menu
"@{"Settings/Show screen title bar" LINK m2titl}" to show / hide it. When the bar
is visible, you can also read the gadget help. This menu has the shortcut
Right-Amiga-S.

The height of the IFF picture decides, whether your screen uses the high
resolution or not. When no valid picture is available, COMPACT uses a screen
with 4 colours, and the Y-resolution is dependent from the tooltype @{"SCRLACED" LINK Tool_SCRLACED}.

PLEASE NOTE: When the high resolution is used, COMPACT tries to use the
"helvetica 18"-font, otherwise "topaz 8" will be used. If "helvetica 18" is
not available (it comes with the Workbench, so everybody should possess it),
the "topaz 8" will be used in the high resolution too, but then the gui will
not look as good as with "helvetica 18".
@endnode
@node "m3iffp" "Menu:  Special / Change IFF-picture"
After selecting this menu, a filerequester will appear. Here you can select
an IFF picture for being the background picture of your own custom screen. If
you are working on an public screen (like the Workbench), your own custom
screen will open immediately after selecting your picture. Otherwise the
existing picture will be replaced by the new one.

You also can load a new background picture by using the APPWINDOW feature
of COMPACT. Simply drag an icon of an IFF picture and let it fall to the
window of COMPACT. It is equal as using this menu.


@{U}For the following conditions an empty screen with 4 colours will be opened:@{UU}
  - The file doesn't exist
  - The selected file is not an picture file or it is not in the IFF format.
  - The IFF picture has more than 256 colours (except HAM6 or HAM8)
  - The IFF picture has only 2 colours (it requires at least 4)
  - The width of the IFF picture is bigger than 640 pixels
  - The IFF picture is in 24 bit format
The Y-resolution normally depends on the height of your picture, so when
no picture can be used, the Y-resolution depends on the tooltype @{"SCRLACED" LINK Tool_SCRLACED}.

Please read also at the menu point @{"Settings / Full palette" LINK m2full}.

When the IFF picture is in EHB (Extra Half Bright), COMPACT uses it like a
picture with 64 colors. HAM-pictures are loaded, but please note, that the
gadgets of the player can cause the typical smears of the HAM modi, which
will let look your picture very ugly.
@endnode
@node "m3trli" "Menu:  Special / Own track-window"
When you select this menu, a new window will be opened. In this window you
see a list of all available tracks at the moment. When a program is active,
only the entries of this program are visible. You always see the correct
sequence of your program (or the sequence of the random mode)!
The currently playing track will be highlighted, so you can see at which
position in the sequence you are and which track is the next one etc.

When you click at an entry, this track will be highlighted and its number
appears at the bottom of the window. After a few seconds the actual playing
track will be highlighted again, but the choosen tracknumber is still
visible below the list. When you click to the button "Play this track" the
choosen track will be played. To play a track you can also double click to
the track in the list.

To close the window simply press ESC or use the close-gadget or select the
menu again.
@endnode
@node "m3name" "Menu:  Special / Own window for names"
Opens a small window which can be sized in the X-axis. Here you can read
the composer, the name of the CD and the actual playing track. This window
can be useful when you use the small window of COMPACT, in which you can't
read this informations. To close the window you can use the close-gadget or
you can press ESC. Also you can select the menu once again.
@endnode
@node "m3arex" "Menu:  Special / ARexx..."
When you select this menu, a new window will be opened. Here you will see
the following gadgets:

@{B}ARexx-port enabled@{UB}

This disables / enables the @{"ARexx port" LINK Main_AREXX}. When it is disabled, no ARexx
command will be processed.

@{B}List of scripts@{UB}

In this list you will see all files of the path "PROGDIR:ARexx", so any
ARexx script which is inside this directory will be selectable in this list.
When you need fast access to one or more scripts, you should put them into
this path.

@{B}Start list@{UB}

When you use this button, the selected ARexx script in the upper list will
be executed.

@{B}Start file@{UB}

With this button you can select an ARexx script in a file requester. It can
be in any path, and after you've accepted the requester, it will be started.
With this method you can execute ARexx scripts which aren't placed in the
ARexx drawer of COMPACT, so you can also use scripts which control functions
of other programs than COMPACT.
@endnode
@node "m3colo" "Menu:  Special / Change colours"
When you select this menu, a new window will be opened. Here you can change
the first 4 colours, which are used to draw the gadgets.
To use the defined colours, you can simply close the window by clicking to
the close-gadget or by pressing ESC (or by selecting the menu once again).
If you prefer to use the default colours you can use the button "DEFAULTS".
You can save the colour-definitions of the first 4 colours to a file. This
file will be loaded at the start of COMPACT, so your colours will be there
at the next start of the player. With the gadget "LOAD" your actual colour
definitions will be replaced with the colours specified in this file, which
always has the name "Compact.col".


At the bottom half of the window you can see a few gadgets, which are useful
when using the colour-cycling of COMPACT:

With the gadget "CYCLE" you switch on/off the colour-cycling, which cycles
all colours of the background-picture (except the first four) in the
sequence defined by the gadget at the right side (forwards or backwards).
The speed of the cycling can be controlled by the slider "Distance", which
can set the speed to values between 1 and 10. Please note, that the cycling
can be activated also by pressing TAB, independent whether this window is
opened or not!

When you have colour-cycled a picture which has no colours suitable for
colour-cycling, you can restore the original colours by using the gadget
"Reload", which loads the colour-part of the IFF picture and sets to
palette to it.

The modes of the color-cycling gadgets are saved along with the config-file
(Menu @{"Settings / Save configuration..." LINK m2save}), so when you start COMPACT again,
they will be like saved before.
@endnode


@node "m3data" "Menu:  Special / Database"
To activate the database of COMPACT, you must use the menu "Special/Database",
which will open the database window. Here the main part is a list of all CDs
in your actual path for the ID-files (see menu @{"Settings/Save-Load-path" LINK m2path}).
When you change this path, the window will be closed and the list of the CDs
will be removed from memory.

At the first start of the database this list is empty, because all ID-files
in the actual path must be read before they can be used here. And this is
also the concept of COMPACT's database: It can't change the contents of the
ID-files, and the contents of the database are always the same as all ID-
files together. It can be used to output selectable fields to a file or to
a printer, or to search for different things of your CDs etc.


To read all ID-files and display it in the list, you must click at the
button "Create list". After that, all data of the ID-files without the
track names and the track times (they are read back when needed) are stored
in the memory. When you click this gadget again, the memory will be
cleared and a new read like described above will be performed. To clear
the memory you can use the gadget "Clear list", but this isn't necessary,
because COMPACT frees all used memory at the end of its work automatically.

@{U}Please note:@{UU} When you type in the data of a new CD (see @{"title input" LINK MaWiTite}), the
data of this CD is copied to the database when you close that window, so
there is no need to read in the whole list again!

You can close the window of the database at every time by clicking to the
close gadget, by pressing ESC or by selecting the menu again. Closing the
database window will NOT cause clearing the memory! When you open the window
again, the list of all CDs will be like before you closed it.

To scroll through the list of all CDs, you can use the slider bar at the
right side of the list. The list contains always the composer and the name
of the CD. To see all tracks and other infos to a CD, you must select the CD
and press "Show CD", which opens the @{"CD-window" LINK windCDTracks} with all infos about it.
This can also be done by double clicking to the CD entry in the list.
Selecting a CD in the database will also display informations about it in
the @{"statistic window" LINK Statisti}, as long as it is opened and the data-source is set to
database there (see the button "STAT" below).

@{B}At the bottom of the window there is a group of gadgets to control different
things for the database:@{UB}

- The cycle gadget with a "F:" in front of it can be used as a @{FG shine}filter@{FG text}. At
  the start its content is "----", which means that no filter is used. You
  can change it to "Singer", "Group", "Sampler", "Maxi" and "Soundtrack",
  and these are the same @{"categories" LINK NameCate}, which are defined in the @{"title input" LINK MaWiTite} of
  a CD.
  After each click to this gadget, the list of the CDs will be updated, so
  only CDs matching this filter will be displayed and used for further
  operations.

  In the title of the database window you can see the number of CDs in the
  actual filter and the number of all CDs in the whole database. For example,
  if the display shows you "45 / 120", this means that the whole database
  contains 120 CDs, and 45 are visible because they are matching the filter.
  When no filter is active, both values are equal.

- After clicking to the "@{FG shine}Output@{FG text}" gadget you will be asked, whether the output
  should go to the printer or to a file. After that selection, all CDs of the
  current list will be transferred to the output destination. To define,
  which fields are used at the output, please read the section about the
  @{"database settings" LINK "m3dbse" 59}. When all CDs are written, a information window will
  tell you that.

- To delete a CD from the memory list (the ID-file will NOT be deleted), you
  can select this CD and click at the button "@{FG shine}Del@{FG text}". This can be useful, when
  this CD should not appear in an output.

- With the gadget "@{FG shine}Cfg@{FG text}" you can open the window for the @{"database settings" LINK m3dbse}.
  It is equal as selecting the menu "Special/Database-Settings".

- With the gadget "@{"EDIT" LINK MaWiTite}"  you can change the ID file of the selected CD,
  without the need to insert this CD into the player.

- To display @{B}statistical informations@{UB} about the actual CD / the selected CD
  in the database, you can press the "@{"STAT" LINK Statisti}" gadget. This opens a new window,
  which displays the TOP10, a graphical display of the track-lengths and
  informations about the CD.

@{B}In top of these gadgets there is an area with multiple gadgets. They can be
used to search for different things in the list of your CDs. The best way to
explain them is from left to right:@{UB}

- The first gadget displays the @{FG shine}field@{FG text}, which is used to search the data. It
  can show the following fields:

  @{B}NAME:@{UB}		The data will be searched in the name fields, which can be
		the COMPOSER, the NAME OF THE CD, and ALL TRACK-NAMES. In
		the window for @{"database settings" LINK "m3dbse" 43} you can define, which of
		these are used for searching.

  @{B}YEAR:@{UB}		The data will be searched in the field for the creation year
		of the CD. Please use always four numbers for the year,
		because otherwise your search could be unsuccessful.

  @{B}CD-TIME:@{UB}	Here you search for the total playing time of a CD. The
		format to write the time is "MM:SS", which means that you
		must use two numbers for the minutes, any character for the
		separator, and two numbers for the seconds.

  @{B}TR-TIME:@{UB}	Here you search for the playing time of the tracks at the CD.
		The format to write the time is "MM:SS" again.

- The next gadget is the @{FG shine}operator@{FG text} to use for your search, and it is only
  usable, when the field gadget is NOT set to "NAME", because the name is
  always searched as "not case sensitive" and "included" (this means, it can
  be at any position inside the text, and the case of the characters is not
  important).
  It can be set to one of the following:

  @{B}=@{UB}	The data of the CD must be exactly the data you search for
  @{B}>@{UB}	The data of the CD must be bigger than the data you search for
  @{B}<@{UB}	The data of the CD must be smaller than the data you search for
  @{B}<>@{UB}	The data of the CD must not be equal the data you search for
  @{B}=>@{UB}	The data of the CD must be bigger or equal the data you search for
  @{B}<=@{UB}	The data of the CD must be smaller or equal the data you search for

- The next on is a @{FG shine}text gadget@{FG text}. Here you can type in the data you wish to
  search in the field you specified at the left side, using the operator
  explained above. When you typed in your data, the two little gadgets at
  the left and the right side are activated. When you click to one of these,
  the search will be started, beginning at the actual selected CD, and
  continuing in the direction specified by the gadget ("<" backwards from
  actual position, ">" forwards from actual position). When no CD is
  selected, the first one at the top of the list will be used as starting
  point.

  When the search was successful, the CD found will be selected. To continue
  the same search starting from this position, simply click to the
  appropriate gadget again. When no entries are found, a window will tell
  you that.
  Please note, that this behaviour will be different from that, when the
  "Multi-Search" option is activated in the @{"database settings" LINK "m3dbse" 13}!

@endnode
@node "m3dbse" "Menu:  Special / Database-Settings"
Here you can define the settings of the database. You can save and load the
settings defined here by using the gadgets "SAVE" and "LOAD", which causes
an access to the file "PROGDIR:Compact.DB". When you start the player, it
looks for this file and all settings stored there will be used automatically.
With the gadget "USE" you can accept all settings and they are usable in the
database, with "CANCEL" nothing will be changed. To close the window, you
also can use its close gadget, press ESC or choosing the menu (all these
things are equal to pressing "CANCEL").
When the switch "USE closes window" is activated, the window will be closed
after clicking to "USE". Otherwise it remains opened, which can be useful
when you try out different output fields etc.

At the top of the window you see the switch @{FG shine}"Multi-Search"@{FG text}, which is useful
when searching in the database:

- @{B}*** Multi-Search is not activated ***@{UB}

  When you perform a search command, COMPACT searches from the actual
  selected database entry in the choosen direction, and when it finds a
  matching entry, this one will be selected in the list. When you click the
  search button again, the search will be continued from this new position.

- @{B}*** Multi-Search is activated ***@{UB}

  When you perform a search command, COMPACT searches from the actual
  selected database entry in the choosen direction, and when it finds a
  matching entry, the @{"window of all tracks" LINK windCDTracks} for this CD will be opened, like
  when you click to "Show CD" in the database window. Then the search will
  be continued automatically, and for all matching entries the window of the
  CD will be opened, until the end of the list will be reached.

  New windows will be opened below the previous one, so you can see the
  window title bar, which shows you the composer and the name of the CD.
  To close all windows, you can close the database window by deselecting it
  in the menu, which causes that all CD-windows will be closed too. Of
  course you can close the windows also by selecting its close gadgets or by
  pressing ESC at every one.

Right beside this gadget you can choose the @{FG shine}sort direction@{FG text} of the CD list,
which can be ascending or descending. This setting will be used also in the
output to a file or a printer.

In the right top side of the window you can select, which fields should be
used when @{FG shine}searching for "NAME"@{FG text}:

- Search COMPOSER:  The field "composer" will be used for searching
- Search CD-NAME:   The field "CD-name" will be used for searching
- Search TRACKS:    All tracknames will be used for searching

Please note, that at least one of them must be selected, because otherwise
no field would be used for searching.
Please note also, that the data of COMPOSER and CD-NAME is stored always in
the memory of the database, so a search will be very fast, because no disk
access is needed. When the TRACKNAMES are included in the search for names,
the database have to read all ID-files to get the names of the tracks, so
the search will take a little more time (approximately 4 seconds for 100 CDs
with my harddisk).

In the middle of the window there are two lists. In the left list you can see
all available fields, which can be used in the @{FG shine}output to a file or a printer@{FG text},
in the right one you see the currently selected fields, which will be used
for the output. They will be used in the order from top to bottom, separated
by the field separator (explained later).
You can add fields to the right list by clicking to them in the left list.
They will be appended to the end of the right list. To delete a field from
the right list, simply double click on it in the right list. To delete all
fields of the right list, you can use the gadget "Clear" at the right side
of the lists.
Please note as stated above, that when you include the tracknames or the times
of the tracks, an access to disk is necessary, so the output will take
a little more time than without these fields.

When the button @{FG shine}"Header"@{FG text} at the right side of the lists is activated, the
output will be started with two lines of basic information about the
following data, which contains the actual filter, the date of the output etc.
When the output for example is designated for making an import to an other
database, you can deactivate this option, so only the fields defined in the
list will be used for the output.

There exists two gadgets for the @{FG shine}field separator@{FG text}, which is used in the
output to separate the fields:

- In the left gadget, you can see and change the ASCII code of the character
  to use as the field separator. After pressing RETURN, the right gadget
  will also be updated.
  When your ASCII code is negative (prefixed with an "-"), one space
  character will be BEFORE your field separator, and one AFTER it. This in
  most cases makes sense, when your output should be printed, because an
  import to an other database will probably need only one char as field
  separator.

  In the right gadget, you can see and change the character directly, so when
  you for example type in "*", the ASCII code for this character (42) will
  be shown in the left gadget. When the previous ASCII code was negative,
  the new ASCII code will be negative too.

When the tracknames of a CD are included in the output list, these names
are treated as one field, so before the tracks and after it there will be the
character for the field separator, but the track names are separated always
by a newline character (ASCII code 10).
@endnode


@node "m3help" "Menu:  Special / AmigaGuide-Help"
This opens the help document you are reading at this moment. Please read
@{"here" LINK Main_KEYBOARD 38} to see how the online help can be accessed too.
@endnode
@node "m3setb" "Menu:  Special / Set Book-mark"
The menu opens a sub menu with 10 entries. When you select one of these, the
actual playing position will be stored at this bookmark. To jump to exactly
this position, you can use the menu "@{"Special / Use Book-mark" LINK m3useb}".
@endnode
@node "m3useb" "Menu:  Special / Use Book-mark"
Opens a sub menu with 10 entries. At the start of COMPACT all entries are
ghosted, so you can not select it. When you store a playing position by using
the menu "@{"Special / Set Book-mark" LINK m3setb}", this entry will be made available for
selection. You can read here the number of the entry and the time-position
of it. For fast access the sub menus can be used by shortcuts too (RAmiga-0
to RAmiga-9)!

These entries will be set automatically, when you saved them in the ID-file
of the actual CD, which can be done in the window @{"Title input" LINK MaWiTite}.

Below these 10 entries you can select "Delete all bookmarks", which will set
all entries to their default contents, which is zero.
@endnode
@node "m3pubs" "Menu:  Special / PubScreen-Jump"
Opens a window with a list of all available public screens, without the one
you are using at the moment. You can select a screen by clicking at its name.
If you want to use all windows of COMPACT at this public screen, you must
click to the gadget "USE IT" below the list. If this screen is available at
the moment you press the gadget, COMPACT will open its windows at this
screen. Also this screen will be made to the frontmost screen. Instead of
clicking at "USE IT" you can also double click to the screen name in the list
you want to jump to.

To define a public screen which should be used at every time COMPACT is
started, you can use the tooltype @{"PUBNAME" LINK Tool_PUBNAME}.

To close the window you can use the close-gadget or you can press ESC. Also
you can select the menu once again.
@endnode

@node "windCDTracks" "CD-window for the tracks of a CD in the database"
This window will be opened when you press the gadget "Show CD" in the window
of the database, or it will be opened by COMPACT itself, when MULTISEARCH is
enabled and a search was successful. It displays all informations about
the selected CD:

The title of this window shows you the composer and the name of the CD.
You can see the number of the tracks, the creation year of the CD, the total
playing time, the recording technology and the ID filename. Under this area
is a string gadget which contains the comment. To read the whole comment,
you can click to the gadget and move the cursor to the left or the right, or
you can size the window to make the gadget bigger/smaller too.

Under the comment is a list of all tracks available at the CD. When you
click at a track, the playing time of it will appear at the bottom of the
window.

At the right side on the top of the window you can see informations about
how often you heard this CD in COMPACT, and the data you first respectively
last heard this CD. This only work with Audio-CDs; with Data-CDs there will
be displayed nothing. To reset this counter to zero, or view more statistical
informations about your CDs (TOP10 for example), you can click at the "STAT"-
gadget in the database window, which opens the @{"statistics window" LINK Statisti}.

To close the window you can use the close-gadget or you can press ESC.
@endnode


## -------------------------------

@node "Main_AREXX" "The ARexx interface"
COMPACT has an ARexx port, so you can control the player via this programming
language. The name of the port is @{B}COMPACT@{UB} (please note that the name is
case sensitive).

A command returns 0 when all is okay. Errors with an ARexx command or an
ARexx function will be returned with 5, false or missing arguments are
returned with 10. Normally ARexx breaks the program at an error >= 10, so if
you don't want that, you must change the boundary value to a number higher
than 10 (see @{"here" LINK ARexx_Info1} for more infos about checking errors and ARexx in general).

  @{"Important information" LINK AREXX_OUTPUT} about data output in the scripts.

For detailed informations to a command please refer to the explanation of
its gadget or menu equivalent.


   @{B}List of all ARexx commands:@{UB}

	@{"APPEAR" LINK rx_appear}
	@{"COLCYC" LINK rx_colcyc}
	@{"EJECT" LINK rx_eject}
	@{"HIDE" LINK rx_hide}
	@{"JUMP" LINK rx_jump}
	@{"PAUSE" LINK rx_pause}
	@{"PLAY" LINK rx_play}
	@{"QUIT" LINK rx_quit}
	@{"RELOADIFFCOL" LINK rx_reloadiffcol}
	@{"SEARCH+" LINK rx_searchp}
	@{"SEARCH-" LINK rx_searchm}
	@{"SETCYCDIR" LINK rx_setcycdir}
	@{"SETCYCDIST" LINK rx_setcycdist}
	@{"SETIFFNAME" LINK rx_setiffname}
	@{"SETPREVIEW" LINK rx_setpreview}
	@{"SHIFTCOL" LINK rx_shiftcol}
	@{"SHOWTEXT" LINK rx_showtext}
	@{"SKIP+" LINK rx_skipp}
	@{"SKIP-" LINK rx_skipm}
	@{"SNAP1" LINK rx_snap1}
	@{"SNAP2" LINK rx_snap2}
	@{"SNAP1CLR" LINK rx_snap1clr}
	@{"SNAP2CLR" LINK rx_snap2clr}
	@{"STOP" LINK rx_stop}
	@{"ZOOM" LINK rx_zoom}

   @{B}List of all ARexx functions:@{UB}

	@{"ACTTRACK" LINK rx_acttrack}
	@{"NUMTRACKS" LINK rx_numtracks}
	@{"CDINSERTED" LINK rx_cdinserted}
	@{"CDTIME" LINK rx_cdtime}
	@{"GETDEVICE" LINK rx_getdevice}
	@{"GETIDPATH" LINK rx_getidpath}
	@{"GETIFFNAME" LINK rx_getiffname}
	@{"GETNAME" LINK rx_getname}
	@{"GETPREVIEW" LINK rx_getpreview}
	@{"GETPUBSCR" LINK rx_getpubscr}
	@{"GETRANDOM" LINK rx_getrandom}
	@{"GETREPEAT" LINK rx_getrepeat}
	@{"GETWINMODE" LINK rx_getwinmode}
	@{"PLAYMODE" LINK rx_playmode}
	@{"PROPMODE" LINK rx_propmode}
	@{"SEARCHSECS" LINK rx_searchsecs}
	@{"SLIDERPROZ" LINK rx_sliderproz}
	@{"SNAPPOS" LINK rx_snappos}
	@{"TRACKSTART" LINK rx_trackstart}
	@{"TRACKTIME" LINK rx_tracktime}

@endnode
@node "AREXX_OUTPUT" "Important information about data output in the scripts"
When your script have to write something to the screen, you can use the
ARexx command SAY. The output of this command will be written to the SHELL-
window, in which you startet COMPACT. But when you startet COMPACT in the
Workbench, there is no SHELL-window to output the data to! In this case, all
data of your SAY commands can't be read anywhere.

Therefore it is better to open an own window in your ARexx script, and output
all data to it. Here you will see an example of an ARexx script, which outputs
data to a console window, which is opened first by itself:


/*-------------------------------------------------------------------*/
/* Outputs the time of all tracks */
OPTIONS RESULTS
ADDRESS 'COMPACT'
numtracks 0
tracks=result

if ~open('handle','CON:0/11/640/200/ARexx/WAIT/CLOSE','W') then exit

do i=1 to tracks
  tracktime 3 i
  min=WORD(result,1)
  sek=WORD(result,2)
  writeln('handle',"Track" i||":  " min sek)
end

cdtime 1
min=WORD(result,1)
sek=WORD(result,2)
writeln('handle',"Total time:" min sek)

dummy=close('handle')
exit
/*-------------------------------------------------------------------*/


As you can see, the console window will be opened by the ARexx script itself,
and in the line with "CON: ...." you can define the dimensions of the window
by yourself. With the ARexx command "writeln" you can write a line of text
to the window, followed automatically with a linefeed-character. When you
don't want the linefeed at the end of your text, you can use the ARexx
command "writech", which only writes your text and nothing more.

The window will remain open after the script has finished, so you have to
close it by clicking at its close gadget, or typing "CTRL \\" at the key-
board. The close gadget is only present, when you use the text "/CLOSE"
within the opening command of "CON:" (like in the script above)!
@endnode
@node "ARexx_Info1" "Infos to ARexx in general"
To increase the value ARexx breaks the script, you can use the command

	OPTIONS FAILAT 11

in the beginning of your script, so you can react on all error values from
COMPACT (0=No error, 5=Error with an ARexx command or function, 10=False or
missing argument) by checking the global ARexx variable "RC", which holds
these error codes. This can be done by checking the variable directly
after a command (IF RC>0 THEN...). If you don't want this, you can omit
the command "OPTIONS FAILAT...", but therefore you can activate the
interrupt handling of ARexx:  SIGNAL ON ERROR  jumps to the label ERROR:
when the variable RC is bigger than 0,  SIGNAL ON FAILURE  jumps to the
label FAILURE: when RC is bigger or equal FAILAT (which is normally 10).


Also you should use the command  OPTIONS RESULTS  in the beginning of your
ARexx-script, when you want to get a result from a function. These results
are always stored in the ARexx variable RESULT. When multiple results are
returned by a function, you must split the result to single values by
using the WORD function of ARexx.


	@{B}@{U}Short example of an ARexx program for COMPACT:@{UB}@{UU}


/* A comment must be there! */

OPTIONS RESULTS		/* Enable results from a function */
OPTIONS FAILAT 11	/* No break when RC=10 */
ADDRESS 'COMPACT'	/* The port name of the player */

'NUMTRACKS 0'		/* Ask for the number of tracks on the whole CD */
say 'There are '||result||' Tracks on the CD'

'CDTIME 1'		/* Ask for the total playing time of the CD */
min=WORD(result,1)	/* Store the minutes in variable "min" */
sec=WORD(result,2)	/* Store the seconds in variable "sec" */
say 'Total playing time is '||min||' minutes and '||sec||' seconds'
say 'This is equal to '||min*60+sec||' seconds'

exit			/* Quit the ARexx script */
@endnode

@node "rx_appear" "ARexx command:  APPEAR"
Syntax:		APPEAR
Function:	When COMPACT is hidden, its window will opened again.
Options:	---
Result:		---
NOTE:		You must wait for at least 1 second between this and the next
		ARexx command! Otherwise the next command may not work
		correctly!
See also:  @{"ARexx command  HIDE" LINK rx_hide}
@endnode
@node "rx_colcyc" "ARexx command:  COLCYC"
Syntax:		COLCYC <mode>
Function:	Switch on/off the colour cycling on your own custom screen.
Options:	<mode>	0 = Switch off colour cycling
			1 = Switch on colour cycling
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Menu Special/Change colours" LINK m3colo}
@endnode
@node "rx_eject" "ARexx command:  EJECT"
Syntax:		EJECT
Function:	Open / close the drawer of your CD-ROM drive.
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget EJECT" LINK MaWiEjec}
@endnode
@node "rx_hide" "ARexx command:  HIDE"
Syntax:		HIDE
Function:	Hide the window of COMPACT. Only an appicon will be visible
		at the Workbench, when defined via tooltype @{"APPICON" LINK TOOL_APPICON}.
Options:	---
Result:		---
NOTE:		You must wait for at least 1 second between this and the next
		ARexx command! Otherwise the next command may not work
		correctly!
See also:  @{"Menu Project/Hide" LINK m1hide}
@endnode
@node "rx_jump" "ARexx command:  JUMP"
Syntax:		JUMP <mm:ss>
Function:	Jump to a new position on CD and start playing there.
Options:	<mm:ss>		mm = minutes, ss = seconds
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget JUMP" LINK MaWiJump}
@endnode
@node "rx_pause" "ARexx command:  PAUSE"
Syntax:		PAUSE
Function:	Switch on/off the pause mode.
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget PAUSE" LINK MaWiPaus}
@endnode
@node "rx_play" "ARexx command:  PLAY"
Syntax:		PLAY [<tracknumber>]
Function:	Start playing at the start of the specified track. When no
		tracknumber is given, the player will start using track 1.
Options:	[<tracknumber>]		Optional tracknumber to start playing
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget PLAY" LINK MaWiPlay}
@endnode
@node "rx_quit" "ARexx command:  QUIT"
Syntax:		QUIT
Function:	Quits the player. It can be possible, that COMPACT sends a
		"STOP"-command to the drive before it quits (see the
		configfile-entry @{"QUITSTOP" LINK Tool_QUITSTOP}).
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Menu Project/Quit" LINK m1quit}
@endnode
@node "rx_reloadiffcol" "ARexx command:  RELOADIFFCOL"
Syntax:		RELOADIFFCOL
Function:	When an own custom screen is active, and the colours are not
		like in the original picture (because you tried a colour
		cycling for example), you can restore the colour palette by
		using this command.
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Menu Special/Change colours" LINK m3colo}
@endnode
@node "rx_searchp" "ARexx command:  SEARCH+"
Syntax:		SEARCH+
Function:	This command continues the playback of your CD at a few
		seconds after the current position. You can change the number
		of seconds via the menu "@{"Settings/SEARCHSECONDS" LINK m2sear}".
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget SEARCH>" LINK MaWiSea+}
@endnode
@node "rx_searchm" "ARexx command:  SEARCH-"
Syntax:		SEARCH-
Function:	This command continues the playback of your CD at a few
		seconds before the current position. You can change the number
		of seconds via the menu "@{"Settings/SEARCHSECONDS" LINK m2sear}".
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget <SEARCH" LINK MaWiSea-}
@endnode
@node "rx_setcycdir" "ARexx command:  SETCYCDIR"
Syntax:		SETCYCDIR <mode>
Function:	Sets the direction of the colour cycling mode on own custom
		screens.
Options:	<mode>	0 = forewards
			1 = backwards
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Menu Special/Change colours" LINK m3colo}
@endnode
@node "rx_setcycdist" "ARexx command:  SETCYCDIST"
Syntax:		SETCYCDIST <distance>
Function:	Sets the distance of colours between two colour cyling loops,
		and therefore you can control the speed of colour cycling.
Options:	<distance>	Must be between 1 and 10
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Menu Special/Change colours" LINK m3colo}
@endnode
@node "rx_setiffname" "ARexx command:  SETIFFNAME"
Syntax:		SETIFFNAME <path/name>
Function:	Specify a new name for the background picture of your own
		custom screen. If COMPACT runs on a public screen like the
		Workbench, a new custom screen will be opened with your
		background picture. If COMPACT runs already on an own custom
		screen, only the background picture will be changed.
Options:	<path/name>
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Menu Special/Change IFF-picture" LINK m3iffp}
@endnode
@node "rx_setpreview" "ARexx command:  SETPREVIEW"
Syntax:		SETPREVIEW <seconds>
Function:	Set the number of seconds to use in preview mode.
Options:	<seconds>	Must be between 1 to 999
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget Preview" LINK MaWiPrev}
@endnode
@node "rx_shiftcol" "ARexx command:  SHIFTCOL"
Syntax:		SHIFTCOL <distance>
Function:	Shift the colour palette to the offset <distance>. To get
		back the original palette you can set it to 0. This call is
		equal as performing <distance> times a colour cycling in the
		specified direction.
Options:	<distance>	Must be between 1 and 251, respectively
				between -1 and -251.
Result:		---
@endnode
@node "rx_showtext" "ARexx command:  SHOWTEXT"
Syntax:		SHOWTEXT <text>
Function:	Opens a requester and displays the <text>. The requester will
		be closed, when the user clicks at the OKAY button. As long as
		the requester is open, COMPACT will not react to anything!
Options:	<text>		Text to display (upto 150 characters).
Result:		---
@endnode
@node "rx_skipp" "ARexx command:  SKIP+"
Syntax:		SKIP+
Function:	You can skip to the track after the actual playing one by
		using this command. The player then will start playing at the
		beginning of the new track, except the player is just paused.
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget SKIP>|" LINK MaWiSki+}
@endnode
@node "rx_skipm" "ARexx command:  SKIP-"
Syntax:		SKIP-
Function:	You can skip to the track before the actual playing one by
		using this command. The player then will start playing at the
		beginning of the new track, except the player is just paused.
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget |<SKIP" LINK MaWiSki-}
@endnode
@node "rx_snap1" "ARexx command:  SNAP1"
Syntax:		SNAP1 [<mm:ss>]
Function:	Set the marker 1 to the actual physical playing time. When an
		argument is specified, set it to this time.
Options:	[<mm:ss>]	mm = minutes, ss = seconds
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget SNAP" LINK MaWiSnap}
@endnode
@node "rx_snap2" "ARexx command:  SNAP2"
Syntax:		SNAP2 [<mm:ss>]
Function:	Set the marker 2 to the actual physical playing time. When an
		argument is specified, set it to this time.
Options:	[<mm:ss>]	mm = minutes, ss = seconds
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget SNAP" LINK MaWiSnap}
@endnode
@node "rx_snap1clr" "ARexx command:  SNAP1CLR"
Syntax:		SNAP1CLR
Function:	Clear the marker for snap-point 1.
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget SNAP" LINK MaWiSnap}
@endnode
@node "rx_snap2clr" "ARexx command:  SNAP2CLR"
Syntax:		SNAP2CLR
Function:	Clear the marker for snap-point 2.
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget SNAP" LINK MaWiSnap}
@endnode
@node "rx_stop" "ARexx command:  STOP"
Syntax:		STOP
Function:	Stops the playing of the CD-ROM drive.
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Gadget STOP" LINK MaWiStop}
@endnode
@node "rx_zoom" "ARexx command:  ZOOM"
Syntax:		ZOOM
Function:	When the player runs on the Workbench or an other public
		screen, this command changes between the normal (big) window
		and the small one. This is the same as pressing the zoom-
		gadget on the window.
Options:	---
Result:		---
See also:  @{"Main window" LINK Main_WINDOW}
@endnode


@node "rx_acttrack" "ARexx function:  ACTTRACK"
Syntax:		ACTTRACK <mode>
Function:	Get the actual playing track number (starting with 1) of the
		whole CD or the actual program.
Options:	<mode>	0 = Get back track number of the whole CD
			1 = Get back track number of the actual program
Result:		Tracknumber as specified, or -1, when no CD is in drive.
		When the player is stopped, 0 will be returned.
@endnode
@node "rx_numtracks" "ARexx function:  NUMTRACKS"
Syntax:		NUMTRACKS <mode>
Function:	Get the number of tracks available on CD or in the actual
		program.
Options:	<mode>	0 = Get back number of tracks on whole CD
			1 = Get back number of tracks in the actual program
Result:		Number of tracks as specified, or -1, when no CD is in drive
@endnode
@node "rx_cdinserted" "ARexx function:  CDINSERTED"
Syntax:		CDINSERTED
Function:	Ask whether a CD is in the drive or not.
Options:	---
Result:		When the function returns 0, no CD is in the drive. Otherwise
		it returns 1.
@endnode
@node "rx_cdtime" "ARexx function:  CDTIME"
Syntax:		CDTIME <mode>
Function:	Get the time of whole CD as specified by mode.
Options:	<mode>	0 = Time since start of CD
			1 = Total playing time of the CD
			2 = Remaining time till the end of the CD
Result:		<minutes> <seconds> or -1, when no CD is in the drive.
NOTE:		When a program is active, the time results depends on the
		settings of menu "@{"Settings / TotalTime = Prog" LINK m2totp}"!
@endnode
@node "rx_getdevice" "ARexx function:  GETDEVICE"
Syntax:		GETDEVICE
Function:	Get the name and the unit of the actual used device.
Options:	---
Result:		<devicename> <unit>
See also:  @{"Menu Project/Set Device" LINK m1devi}
@endnode
@node "rx_getidpath" "ARexx function:  GETIDPATH"
Syntax:		GETIDPATH
Function:	Get the path which is used for saving/loading the ID-files.
Options:	---
Result:		<path>
See also:  @{"Menu Settings/Save-Load-path" LINK m2path}
@endnode
@node "rx_getiffname" "ARexx function:  GETIFFNAME"
Syntax:		GETIFFNAME
Function:	Get the path and name of the IFF file, which is used as a
		background picture for your own custom screen.
Options:	---
Result:		<path/name>
See also:  @{"Arexx command SETIFFNAME" LINK rx_setiffname}
@endnode
@node "rx_getname" "ARexx function:  GETNAME"
Syntax:		GETNAME <mode>
Function:	Get the name of the composer, name of CD or the name of the
		actual playing track.
Options:	<mode>	0 = Get the name of the composer
			1 = Get the name of the CD
			2 = Get the name of the actual playing track
Result:		<name>
@endnode
@node "rx_getpreview" "ARexx function:  GETPREVIEW"
Syntax:		GETPREVIEW <mode>
Function:	Ask whether the preview mode is on/off, or how many seconds
		are defined for the preview mode.
Options:	<mode>	0 = Ask whether preview mode is on/off
			1 = Ask the number of seconds to use in preview mode
Result:		Returns 0 for off / 1 for on, respectively the number of
		seconds.
See also:  @{"Gadget PREVIEW" LINK MaWiPrev}
@endnode
@node "rx_getpubscr" "ARexx function:  GETPUBSCR"
Syntax:		GETPUBSCR
Function:	Get the name of the public screen. Will be returned also
		when an own custom screen is just in use.
Options:	---
Result:		<name>
See also:  @{"Tooltype PUBNAME" LINK Tool_PUBNAME}
@endnode
@node "rx_getrandom" "ARexx function:  GETRANDOM"
Syntax:		GETRANDOM
Function:	Ask whether the random mode is on/off.
Options:	---
Result:		Returns 0 for off / 1 for on.
See also:  @{"Gadget RANDOM" LINK MaWiRand}
@endnode
@node "rx_getrepeat" "ARexx function:  GETREPEAT"
Syntax:		GETREPEAT
Function:	Ask whether the repeat mode is on/off.
Options:	---
Result:		Returns 0 for off / 1 for on.
See also:  @{"Gadget REPEAT" LINK MaWiRepe}
@endnode
@node "rx_getwinmode" "ARexx function:  GETWINMODE"
Syntax:		GETWINMODE
Function:	Ask the actual used window mode.
Options:	---
Result:		<mode>	0 = Public screen, normal (big) window
			1 = Public screen, small window
			2 = Own custom screen
			3 = Hidden (no window / screen is used)
@endnode
@node "rx_playmode" "ARexx function:  PLAYMODE"
Syntax:		PLAYMODE
Function:	Get the mode of playing.
Options:	---
Result:		<mode>	0 = Playmode is "Whole CD"
			1 = Playmode is "Program"
			2 = Playmode is "SnapRange"
See also:  @{"Gadget Play-Mode" LINK MaWiPlMd}
@endnode
@node "rx_propmode" "ARexx function:  PROPMODE"
Syntax:		PROPMODE
Function:	Get the mode of the proportional slider
Options:	---
Result:		<mode>	0 = Proportional mode is "Whole CD"
			1 = Proportional mode is "Actual Title"
			2 = Proportional mode is "Program"
			3 = Proportional mode is "Snap Range"
See also:  @{"Gadget Proportional" LINK MaWiPrMd}
@endnode
@node "rx_searchsecs" "ARexx function:  SEARCHSECS"
Syntax:		SEARCHSECS
Function:	Get the number of seconds, which are used when a "SEARCH+" or
		a "SEARCH-" command is used.
Options:	---
Result:		<seconds>
See also:  @{"Menu Settings/SEARCH-Seconds" LINK m2sear}
@endnode
@node "rx_sliderproz" "ARexx function:  SLIDERPROZ"
Syntax:		SLIDERPROZ
Function:	Get the number of percent for the actual slider position.
Options:	---
Result:		<percent>	Ranges from 0 to 100
See also:  @{"Slider-Gadget" LINK MaWiSlid}
@endnode
@node "rx_snappos" "ARexx function:  SNAPPOS"
Syntax:		SNAPPOS <mode>
Function:	Get the stored snappoint time for SNAP1 or SNAP2
Options:	<mode>	1 = Get time for SNAP1
			2 = Get time for SNAP2
Result:		<min> <sec> or -1 for "No CD in drive"
See also:  @{"Gadget SNAP" LINK MaWiSnap}
@endnode
@node "rx_trackstart" "ARexx function:  TRACKSTART"
Syntax:		TRACKSTART [<track>]
Function:	Get the start position of the actual track. When an argument
		is specified, the start position of that track will be
		returned.
Options:	[<track>]	Must be between 1 and biggest track number
Result:		<min> <sec> or -1 for "No CD in drive"
@endnode
@node "rx_tracktime" "ARexx function:  TRACKTIME"
Syntax:		TRACKTIME <mode> [<track>]
Function:	Get the time of actual playing track as specified by mode.
		If <track> is specified, you can get the total playing time
		of this track; in this case the <mode> must be set to 3!
Options:	<mode>	0 = Time since start of track
			1 = Total playing time of the track
			2 = Remaining time till the end of the track
			3 = Total playing time of the track specified
			    in <track>.
		<track>	When the <mode> is 3, you can specify here the
			track number you want to examine. You can only get
			the total playing time of it.
Result:		<minutes> <seconds> or -1, when no CD is in the drive.
@endnode

@node "Statisti" "Database: Statistics"
@{B}(Please read also the "Additional note" at the end of this page.)@{UB}


In this window, which is opened from the gadget "STAT" in the database, you
can see statistical informations about your CDs. Everytime you insert an
Audio-CD (not with Data-CDs) while COMPACT is running, a counter for this
CD will be increased and stored in a separate file, called "compact.top10".
In this file there is also stored, at which date you heard this CD the first
time, and the date you heard it last.


	@{B}@{FG shine}@{U}THE LEFT SIDE OF THE WINDOW@{UU}@{FG text}@{UB}


With this file COMPACT can find out, how often a CD is heard, and with this
information it can build the TOP10 list, which is displayed at the left side
of the statistic window. If you want to display more than 10 CDs in this
list, you can type it in the gadget above the list, so if you for example
set it to 50, you will see the 50 most heard CDs in the list. The list is
always sorted in descending order, so the most heard CD is on the top. The
number of displayed CDs in the TOP10 list will be stored in the config file
of COMPACT, when saving it (see menu "@{"Settings / Save configuraton" LINK m2save}")

In this list you will first see the counter of the CD, and then the composer
followed by the name of the CD, or the @{"ID-Number" LINK IDnumber} of the CD.
When the CD isn't contained in the @{"Database" LINK m3data}, then the ID-number will be
displayed, because the name of the composer/CD isn't stored in the TOP10-file.
When the CD is contained in the database, it's data will be used to display
the TOP10 list. So it is better to read in the database when displaying the
TOP10 list.


@{U}Below the list there are two gadgets:@{UU}

@{B}DB-Sync@{UB}

With this button you can synchronize the TOP10 file with your database. A new
window will be opened in which you can decide, whether you want to delete
all superfluous TOP10 entries, or only a single one.
For more detailed explanations about this feature, see @{"here" LINK T10Sync}.

@{B}Reset All@{UB}

To reset the counter of all CDs in the TOP10-file (it stores how often you
heard the CD), you can press this button. A security question will be asked
before doing this, because the consequence will be, that the TOP10 list will
be initialized to zero for all CDs.


	@{B}@{FG shine}@{U}THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE WINDOW@{UU}@{FG text}@{UB}


The right side of the statistic window displays information of a CD, and the
switch at the top of the window decides, which CD is used:

@{B}Actual@{UB}

All informations below refers to the actual inserted CD. When no CD is in
the player, no information will be displayed.

@{B}Database@{UB}

All informations below refers to the selected CD in the database. When no
CD is selected, or the database contains no CDs, no information will be
displayed. When you select another CD in the database, the data and graphics
below will be updated immediately.


You can see here the date you first heard (=inserted) the CD, then the date
you last heard it, and the counter how often you heard it. Below there is a
graphical display, which shows you the lengths of the tracks in different
types. The type of the graphic can be selected with the switch below the
graphic:

@{B}Graphic type 1@{UB}

Shows you a rectangle for each track, with the longest track reaching from
bottom to top. Here you can see the relation of the playing time of all
tracks. A horizontal line, which is drawn from left to right, displays the
@{U}average@{UU} playing time of all tracks.

@{B}Graphic type 2@{UB}

Shows you an circle (or ellipse; it depends on the size of the window), and
the perimeter of it corresponds to the playing time of the whole CD. When
you imagine this circle as a clock, the first track starts at 9 o'clock, and
then the time starts in clockwise direction, so track two can start for
example at 11 o'clock or so. To show you this starting point and the
direction, a small indicator is visible at 9 o'clock.
As bigger as the parts of the circle are displayed, as longer is the playing
time of its corresponding track.
For maximum speed in drawing the graphic, only 1 background colour is used.

@{B}Graphic type 3@{UB}

Shows you exactly the same circle as in graphic type 2, only with separate
colours for each track. Because this will take much more time to draw than
the graphic type 2, this graphic type is probably only fast enough on
systems equipped with a graphic card.


Below the graphic there is the button "Reset CD". With this one you can
reset the counter of the CD in the TOP10-file (it stores how often you
heard the CD). A security question will be asked before doing this.


	@{B}@{FG shine}@{U}GENERAL INFORMATIONS ABOUT THE STATISTIC WINDOW@{UU}@{FG text}@{UB}


@{U}In the following cases all contents of the statistic window (or only parts
of it) will be updated automatically:@{UU}

- Ejecting or inserting a CD.
  Causes an update of the right side of the window, as long as it displays
  informations about the actual CD. The TOP10 list and the "heard-counter"
  are updated too, because inserting a CD increases its TOP10 counter.

- Typing in a new title for the actual CD / database CD.
  In this case the TOP10 list must be updated, for the case the actual CD
  is contained in it.

- Selecting a new CD in the database.
  In this case the right side of the window have to be updated, as long as
  it displays informations about a database CD.

- Closing database window  or  New loading/clearing of the database-contents.
  Updates the right side of the window, as long as it displays informations
  about a selected CD of the database.

- Changing the filter of the database.
  Causes an update of the right window side, as long as it displays an
  information about a database CD.


@{B}@{BG shine}  @{U}***** Additional note: *****@{UU}  @{BG back}@{UB}

When you start COMPACT and it can't find the TOP10 file, it tries to create
the file itself. Therefore it opens the database and reads in the contents
of all ID-files, then it creates the TOP10 file and stores all CDs of the
database in it. For all CDs the TOP10-counter is set to zero, and the date
of first/last heard is set to the actual date. After this, COMPACT closes
the datebase, and then the normal startup operation is continued.

Because of this behavior, it could be, that for the first time you start
COMPACT, you will see a short opening/closing of the database window. This
is absolutely normal and does not represent a wrong operation of COMPACT!
After COMPACT can read in the TOP10 file at its startup, no reading of the
database is necessary anymore at startup.

In the case, when COMPACT reads the TOP10 file at startup, and an error
occurs (not enough memory, file corrupt etc.), COMPACT will NOT save the
file of the TOP10 in this session anymore, because saving would destroy the
TOP10 file on disk (and on disk the file is probably without errors).
Therefore an error message will be displayed the next time, COMPACT tries
to save the TOP10 file (depends on menu "@{"Settings / Save TOP10 immediately" LINK m2t10s}").
@endnode

@node "T10Sync" "Database: Statistics - TOP10 Synchronization"
When you press the button "Sync" in the database, a new window will be
opened to synchronize the TOP10 file with your database.

The synchronization is needed for the following case: Everytime you insert
a CD, COMPACT stores its TOP10-information (counter, date of first/last
hearing) in the TOP10 file. For a part of the CDs you type in the composer,
the track names etc. and store it in a file, so COMPACT can display it again
the next time you insert this CD.
But for another part of the CDs you only insert it to hear them, without
typing in the composer and so on. But for these CDs there exists a stored
information in the TOP10-file! It isn't very much amount of data, but if you
want to delete the informations of these type of CDs, you can use the
synchronization feature.

In the new window there is a list with all TOP10 entries, which are not
contained in COMPACT's database - these are the so-called superfluous
entries. Below of this list there are two buttons:

@{B}Delete all@{UB}

When you press it, COMPACT will delete all TOP10 entries in the TOP10-file,
which are not contained in COMPACTs database (and therefore displayed in
the list). So the database and the TOP10-file are synchronized.

@{B}Delete selected@{UB}

With this button you can delete a single selected TOP10 entry from the
TOP10-file. The remaining superfluous entries are remaining in it.
@endnode


